<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0001 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Environment Day Observed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Environment Ministry has set a slogan for the day: "2000,
The Environment Millennium: Time to Act." To mark the Day, the
ministry organized a rally and a procession in the morning, a fair
and a discussion in the afternoon, and a cultural function in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is grappling with arsenic contamination of ground
water and air, river, land and sound pollution. Government
officials openly admitted that the concept of environment itself
is a new addition to the human development programs of the country.
They said they are yet to take professional measures to address
the problems.
</P>
<P>
However, changes are taking place in the country. Civil
societies all over the country have formed groups to disseminate
environment-related messages to the people. Government and non-
governmental organizations are increasingly bound to assess
environmental impact of all their development projects.
</P>
<P>
Now there will be one single focus -- to grow awareness among
the people for whom protecting environment has become a life-and-
death issue.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the World Environment Day, President
Shahabuddin Ahmed called for all concerned to play an active role
in creating mass awareness about the harms of environmental
degradation.
</P>
<P>
"The world community should unitedly face the environmental
problem caused by various facts, including greenhouse effect,
depletion of ozone layer, climate change, desertification, sea-
level rise and global warming," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing hope for the growing public awareness of the
environment across the world, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said
Bangladesh is equally vocal at regional and international levels
like other nations of the world for protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
"Our government is relentlessly trying to protect the
environment and has signed various eco-friendly international
protocols and agreements," the prime minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
