<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Launches Initiative for FTA With Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Singapore and Canada will begin
exploring the possibility of negotiating a bilateral free trade
agreement (FTA) between them, Singapore Ministry of Trade and
Industry (MTI) said in a press release Monday.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Trade and Industry George Yeo and Canadian
International Trade Minister Pierre Pettigrew announced the
initiative in Darwin, Australia, on the sidelines of the Meeting
of APEC Ministers Responsible for Trade, MTI said.
</P>
<P>
The Canada-Singapore FTA will be the second FTA initiative
Singapore is launching with countries across the Pacific Ocean.
George Yeo recently announced that FTA negotiations with Mexico
would commence in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
Yeo was quoted as saying in an interview following his meeting
with Pettigrew that a FTA would send a strong signal to
Singaporeans on the future prospects of further developing links
between the two countries in trade, investment, science and
technology, culture, education and people-to-people contact.
</P>
<P>
He was also quoted as affirming that the proposed Canada-
Singapore FTA will help bring both sides of the Pacific closer
together.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed the hope that the exploration with
Canada will lead to the launch of negotiations later in the year
and, bit by bit, will bring both sides of the Pacific together to
achieve APEC's Bogor vision of free trade and investments by 2010
for developed economies and 2020 for all economies, MTI added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
