<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Unaffected by Earthquake in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Concerned authorities of
Singapore announced that no building in the country was affected
by the tremor arising from the earthquake off the Indonesian
island of Sumatra in early morning Monday.
</P>
<P>
A press release jointly issued Monday by Singapore's Building
and Construction Authority (BCA) and Housing Development Board (
HDB) said that BCA have visually inspected the buildings that were
reportedly affected by the tremor and the inspections did not
reveal any structural damage and there is no reported damage to
the infrastructure such as roads and bridges, and electrical and
communication service.
</P>
<P>
HDB engineers carried out the inspections to 90 HDB apartment
blocks in estates in areas where residents reported that they felt
tremors in their blocks and the results of the inspections show
that the blocks are structurally "sound and safe," it added.
</P>
<P>
The powerful earthquake off Sumatra, measured 7.9 on Richter
scale with epicenter 112 kilometer off the city of Bengkulu on the
west coast of Sumatra, has been felt in Singapore with hundreds of
residents leaving their high rise homes in various parts of the
island.
</P>
<P>
The police and the Civil Defense Force received 600 to 700
calls but no injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
The press release underlined that Singapore is located in a
stable geological formation and is situated more than 400
kilometers from the Indonesian earthquake belt.
</P>
<P>
At such a distance, large earthquakes in Indonesia would cause
minor vibrations or tremors to buildings in Singapore, it said,
assuring that the low-level vibrations would not be significant
enough to cause structural damage or affect the structural
integrity of the buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
