<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Germany will receive 400 former South Lebanon Army
(SLA) militiamen and their family members and allow them to settle
in Germany, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his meeting with Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy, Fischer said the decision of his government is
purely out of humanitarian considerations.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who arrived here on Saturday for a three-day working
visit, was updated by Levy on the latest development of the Middle
East peace process and Israel's troop withdrawal from south
Lebanon. (Israel-Germany-SLA)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrived
in the Middle East Monday afternoon from Moscow, hoping to bridge
the gap between Israelis and the Palestinians in reaching a
framework agreement on final-status issues.
</P>
<P>
This was Albright's first visit to the region since the Sharm el
Sheikh conference last September, and the visit was arranged during
U.S. President Bill Clinton's talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak in Lisbon, Portugal, last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During her two-day mission in the region, Albright is scheduled
to hold talks with Barak later in the evening and meet with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Tuesday. She will also travel
to Egypt to hold talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on her
way home. (Israel-Albright)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli-Palestinian peace talks is the core of the
Middle East peace process after Israeli troop withdrawal from south
Lebanon, said U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright here
Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Israeli-Palestinian problem and the difference
between the two sides can only be solved through negotiations,
Albright told reporters after her talks with Israeli Prime
MinisterEhud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here earlier Monday afternoon from Moscow for a
two-day visit, aimed at narrowing the difference between Israel and
the Palestinians in reaching a framework agreement on final-status
issues. (Israel-Albright-Barak)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- U.N. special envoy Terje Roed-Larsen announced here
Monday night that U.N. cartographers have confirmed the line that
will be used to verify Israel's withdrawal form south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Larsen told reporters following his talks with Lebanese leaders
that the U.N. team has wrapped up setting the line between Israel
and Lebanon. "The U.N. will verify whether Israel's withdrawal from
south Lebanon is complete or not according to the line," Larsen
added.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. experts will end their work on some concerning
part along the line. (Lebanon-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak ordered Monday to
stop the negotiations with the ultra-Orthodox Jewish Shas Party
over its demands for more government money for its financially
ailing educational network.
</P>
<P>
The move came in response to threats by the powerful religious
party to support Knesset (Parliament) member Avigdor Liberman's
bill proposal for early elections, which will be brought to a vote
Wednesday. (Israel-Shas-Negotiations) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
