<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's International Reserves Drop in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's international reserves saw
their largest drop in 15 months in May as the country spent 835
million U.S. dollars on supporting the Canadian dollar and on
other accounts, according to the Finance Department figures.
</P>
<P>
The figures, which were made known Tuesday, show that foreign
currency debt increased 1.037 billion Canadian dollars (about 701
million U.S. dollars), which hit its 10 month low at 66.19 cents(U.
S.) in late May.
</P>
<P>
Returns on investments netted 318 million dollars (about 215
million U.S. dollars), but foreign currency debt charges cost the
government 222 million (about 150 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Total reserves in May were reported to be 29.595 billion
Canadian dollars (about 20 billion U.S. dollars), composed of 21.
738 billion (about 14.693 billion U.S. dollars) in securities, 4.
224 billion(about 2.855 billion U.S. dollars) in deposits, 364
million (about 246 million U.S. dollars) in gold, 545 million (
about 368 million U.S.dollars) in special drawing rights and 2.724
billion (about 1.841 billion U.S. dollars) in reserve in the
International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
