<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Chad-Cameroon Oil Pipeline Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Board of the World Bank
Group on Tuesday agreed to support the highly controversial Chad-
Cameroon Petroleum Development and Pipeline Project.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in a statement it would lend 39.5 million U.S.
dollars to Chad and 53.4 million dollars to Cameroon to help build
a 1,070 kilometer pipeline to carry oil from the Doba field in
southern Chad to loading facilities off Cameroon's Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the International Finance Corporation, the bank
unit making loans to the private sector, will lend 100 million
dollars to the joint venture pipeline and mobilize up to 300
million dollars in syndicated loans from commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Participating oil companies, banks and export credit agencies
would provide the remaining 3.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project has been estimated at 3.7 billion
dollars to develop the Doba fields and build the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
US firms ExxonMobil and Chevron are participating with 40 and
25 percent stakes respectively, as is Malaysia's Petronas, with 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Bank estimates that the project would generate 2 billion
dollars for Chad and 500 million dollars for Cameroon over a 25-
year period.
</P>
<P>
In addition to its pipeline investments, the bank also approved
two projects to help strengthen Chad's and Cameroon's capacities
for environmental management and monitoring of the petroleum
sectors.
</P>
<P>
These would be supported by 23.7 million dollars and 5.8
million dollars in credits from the International Development
Association, the bank's lending arm for the poorest countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
