<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia should build a potent
defense force as a guarantee for its future security, the
country's Army Chief of Staff Tsadikan Gebretensae said here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tsadikan told local reporters that Ethiopia can only rely on
its own capability to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the latest offensive against Eritrea launched
between May 12 and 29, Tsadikan said Ethiopia has put out of
action most of the 24 Eritrean divisions and Eritrean leaders will
have to conduct extensive reconstruction of their army to make up
for the loss sustained.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the air power in the country, Tsadikan said
the Ethiopian air force has now reached a level where it can
effectively undertake any mission, no matter the magnitude of the
enemy's air defense system.
</P>
<P>
This has been demonstrated by the success of the missions it
has executed in recent times targeting Eritrea's military
facilities, including those in the capital Asmara, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest report by spokesperson of Ethiopia,
fighting between Ethiopian and Eritrean troops has been continuing
in the eastern Bure front, where the Ethiopian troops repulsed
attacks by the Eritrean army Tuesday afternoon, causing heavy
casualties to the latter's troops. 
