<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conditions for U.S.-Israeli-Palestinian Summit Still Immature: Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here Tuesday that the conditions for
holding a three-way summit between U.S., Israeli and Palestinian
leaders are still immature.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference after meeting Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy Tuesday afternoon, Albright noted that
all the sides should make efforts to help bring about such a summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Clearing the way for a meeting by the end of June in the United
States between U.S. President Bill Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is reportedly the
major task of Albright's ongoing Middle East tour, which began on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
It has been hoped that such a Camp David-style summit will
produce a final-status framework agreement between Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the United States, Egypt and Israel met in Camp David
in 1979 and hammered out a treaty, the first between an Arab
country and the Jewish state, to realize peace between the two
Middle East powers.
</P>
<P>
Barak had spelled out Israel's stands on the issue Monday night
after meeting with Albright, saying that the three-way summit is
important for pushing forward the peace process, but it could only
be held when Israel's security is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's news conference, Albright pointed out that she and
President Clinton had "rolled up sleeves" to help the two sides
reach a peace plan, but the final decision should be made by
Israeli and Palestinians leaders themselves.
</P>
<P>
During her talks with Arafat earlier Tuesday in the West Bank
city of Ramallah, Albright managed to persuade the Palestinian
leader to accept an arrangement, in which Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators will be sent back to the Washington area early next
week and resume their works on a final settlement there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat will also secure a meeting with Clinton at the
White House next Wednesday, a move aimed to advance the peace
process further after Clinton's meeting with Barak in Portugal last
week.
</P>
<P>
Albright expressed her hope on Tuesday that the Israeli-
Palestinian negotiations will make tangible progress on key final-
status issues, such as the status of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements,
Palestinian refugees, border, security and water, with full-speed
after the resumption.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians launched their intensive peace talks
in March in the United States and moved the talks back to the
region in April. 
</P>
<P>
In May, it was revealed that the two sides had opened a secret
channel in Stockholm, capital of Sweden, to speed up the
finalization of the framework agreement. This channel has also been
moved back to the region by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear immediately that exactly, which channel will be
reopened in Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
Albright termed her Tuesday afternoon's meeting with Levy as "
excellent," as they exchanged views on a wide range of issues
regarding the Israeli-Arab peace tracks.
</P>
<P>
Levy thanked Clinton and Albright for their efforts to promote
the peace process. However, he accused the Palestinians of foot-
dragging the process.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to meet with Barak again Tuesday evening
and will leave here for Cairo Wednesday morning to meet foreign
ministers from Arab countries there, including Syrian Foreign
Minister Faruk Shareh. 
</P>
