<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The World Bank is considering to provide Egypt with
loans totaling 280 million U.S. dollars in the fiscal year 2000-
2001 starting July 1, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Khaled Ikram, director of the bank's Egypt department, told the
news agency that the bank is expected to approve the loans in mid-
June.
</P>
<P>
Of the loans, 80 million dollars will be earmarked for upgrading
Egypt's sanitary system, 100 million dollars for updating higher
education and the rest for industrial development, Ikram said.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The volume of trade between the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) and Turkey increased by 67 percent to over 400
million U.S. dollars in 1999 compared with 1998, according to a
statement from the Turkish Embassy released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate is the third highest among the countries having
trade with Turkey. Turkey's trade with India and Pakistan grew the
highest last year, the UAE official news agency quoted the
statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish economic delegation will visit the UAE from June 9 to
13. The delegation will hold talks with high-level UAE officials
mainly on establishing a UAE-Turkey Business Council and eventually
concluding an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will comprise the prospective Turkish members of
the proposed UAE-Turkey Business Council.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The World Bank will provide Egypt with soft loans
totaling 175 million U.S. dollars under two agreements signed in
Cairo between the two sides on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will allocate the loans for upgrading rural development
and beefing up the private sector's role in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The agreements offered Egypt preferential terms, under which
half the loans are in grants.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and the United States signed here on Sunday a
cooperation agreement on updating and developing the control center
of the Aswan High Dam power station.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulated that the U.S. Agency of International
Development will grant Egypt 17 million U.S. dollars for the
project under the U.S.-Egypt program to develop Egypt's electricity
sector.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Electricity Authority will also provide 10 million
Egyptian pounds (2.9 million dollars) for the renovation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egypt will upgrade the generators of the power
station. The German Reconstruction Bank has agreed to supply a soft
loan of 170 million German marks (104.79 million dollars) for the
project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
