<HEADLINE> IGC Forecasts World Wheat Supply And Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The forecast for world wheat
production is 4 m. lower than last month at 587 m. tons, largely
reflecting reduced estimates for Hungary and Kazakhstan, it was
announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the International Grains Council (IGC) said a crop of
this size would still be 4 m. tons more than in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The forecast for wheat trade is unchanged at 102 m.tons, the
same as in 1999/00. Import requirements are projected to decline
in the CIS, Near East Asia and South Asia, while purchases into
South America, Pacific Asia and North Africa are expected to rise.
</P>
<P>
World wheat consumption is forecast at a record 600 m.tons with
most of the increase in food use in developing countries,
according to the announcement by the IGC.
</P>
<P>
It said wheat stocks are forecast at 6 m. lower than last month
at 105 m. tons, due mainly to the reduction in estimated world
output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
