<HEADLINE> Cuba: Social Advancement Depends On Women's Participation in Sustainable Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- There cannot be social
advancement without public policies which favor the participation
of women in sustainable development with equality, Cuba said here
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the United Nations General
Assembly special session on women, Ms Vilma Espin Guiliois, Member
of the Council of State of Cuba, said five years after the Beijing
Conference on women, important advances can be seen in some
regions and their countries in connection with the implementation
of some areas of the Platform for Action.
</P>
<P>
It was also true that in many places women claimed that this
major document for their progress had been well kept in long
forgotten archives, Guiliois said.
</P>
<P>
"Women's growing social protagonism and the pressures and
demands which have been put on governments by many women
organizations during the process of follow-up on Beijing, have
allowed to show some progress in the promulgation of laws which
acknowledge their political rights, incorporate the principle of
equality in family law," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Some governments have created mechanisms: ministries, offices,
committees which are exclusively mandated to bring about progress
for women," she said.
</P>
<P>
However, she said, women had seen in these past five years how
they were excluded from opportunities to gain access to a
dignified job, an adequate professional and technical training,
health care and the guarantees of social security.
</P>
<P>
 Privatization, adjustment policies, financial crisis and the
International Monetary Fund formula had increased the feminization
of poverty and unemployment, the deprivation of work, and the use
of women as cheap labor force, she said,
</P>
<P>
"These are the most important issues that concern today women
from around the world, often aggravated by the indifference and
ineffectiveness of States weakened by the own neoliberal concept,
lack of political will, resources and development possibilities,"
she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
