<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Secretary Face Pressure in Policing Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary
Peter Mandelson was facing a difficult political balancing act
when he gave more details on the government's plans to reform
Northern Ireland's police force in the House of Commons on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson was under pressure from nationalists and republicans
to ensure the Patten report on policing is implemented, while the
unionist community fears the former Hong Kong governor's proposals
go too far.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is pressing the government to honor its commitments
to implementing the report, while the Conservatives are calling
for the second reading of the Police Bill to be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
There are also fears that if republican concerns are not met on
Patten report, then the Irish Republican Army could withdraw its
co-operation over the inspection of its arms dumps.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein fears that under the Bill, commitments to addressing
the massive imbalance between Protestants and Catholics within the
police force may lapse after three years.
</P>
<P>
And the party is also worried that the reformed force may not
have a new name or badge and that current members of the RUC who
join it will not have to swear an oath committing them to uphold
human rights.
</P>
<P>
While the Tories are set to table an amendment calling for the
second reading of the Bill to be abandoned, Sinn Fein and the
nationalist Social and Democratic Labor Party (SDLP) have both
proposed more than 40 amendments to the Bill, warning that a lack
of alterations would have serious implications for the new
policing service. 
</P>
