<HEADLINE> Annan Proposes to Increase Funds for Iraq's Oil Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 6 (Xinhua -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Tuesday recommended that the Security Council consider a
further addition of 300 million U.S. dollars to the allocation for
Iraq's oil spare parts and equipment for Phase VIII of the oil-for-
food program.
</P>
<P>
Annan's recommendation will bring the total allocation for
that phase to 600 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a written report to the Security Council, Annan welcomed
the decision by the Council to approve the allocation of an
additional 300 million dollars for the purchase of oil spare parts
and equipment for phases VI and VII of the program.
</P>
<P>
"This will assist in addressing the state of deterioration
that characterizes the oil industry in Iraq," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. The oil-for-food program, which began to be
implemented in late 1996, is an exception to the sanctions. The
program allows Iraq to generate a limited amount of funds through
the sale of oil, for the importation of food and basic medicines.
</P>
<P>
Today, Iraq is allowed to export unlimited amounts of oil and
to import a wide range of goods to meet the humanitarian needs of
its population and to rehabilitate its civilian infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the program, the authorized revenue ceiling
was 2 billion dollars in every six months, providing 1.32 billion
for the implementation of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the revenues earned by oil exports during
phase VII, which expires on Thursday, will reach 8.4 billion
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
