<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Back Beef Labelling Formula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- European Union agriculture
ministers on Tuesday adopted a common position regarding the new
labelling formula for beef to be sold on consumer markets across
the union.
</P>
<P>
The new labelling formula is to be materialized in two stages
with the first one starting this Summer and the second one in
January 2002.
</P>
<P>
The slaughterhouses will have to be written on the labels of
beef products in the first stage while the farms where the cattle
is born and raised will have to be labelled as well to give
consumers more details on the traceability of the herd from which
the beef products come from.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has already taken measures as regards the
time the cattle has to be raised to be suitable for producing beef
and de-boned beef products.
</P>
<P>
Computers are used to trace the origins of the cattle and ear
marks are also used to keep track of the animal from birth on to
the slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
Strict measures have to be resorted to after the madcow disease
hit most of the European Union member states, starting from
Britain.
</P>
<P>
A variant form of the madcow disease can also befall upon human
beings who then develop brain malfunctions. So far more than 20
patients have died of the madcow variant disease in Britain.
</P>
<P>
British beef had been banned from exporting to other EU
countries and the European Union has just lifted the ban, with
France still sticking to its ban against the British beef.
</P>
<P>
Cattle brains, eyes, blood and bones are still considered risk
materials to be consumed by human beings and to be used in the
production of animal feed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
