<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Racism Law Passes EU Legialation Threshold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The first anti-racism law in the
European Union on Tuesday passed a major legislation threshold
when the social affairs ministers from EU member states endorsed
it.
</P>
<P>
The new law, when passed by the European Parliament, will put
all EU member states on a similar footing. Britain now already
has domestic anti-racism law whereas Sweden has little.
</P>
<P>
Though the Amsterdam Treaty gave the European Union the power
to adopt legislation to curb or counter discrimination, the
governments of member states will have to define what is meant by
discrimination, give victims means of redress, provide information
about the rights of individuals and monitor discriminative
incidents.
</P>
<P>
The agreement among EU social affairs ministers, said European
Social Affairs Commissioner Anna Diamantopoulou in a statement,was
a clear sign of the commitment of the European Union to the
fundamental rights of the EU citizens.
</P>
<P>
One of the anti-racism law's controversial clauses will shift
the burden of proof in cases of discrimination onto companies and
providers of goods and services that are accused of racism.
</P>
<P>
They then have to prove that they did not discriminate.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's political agreement on the main aspects of the anti-
racism law was achieved just a year after the Amsterdam Treaty was
adopted by all EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Racism is still a social problem in EU member states. An EU
survey has found that more than one third of the respondents to
the questionnaire said that they feel themselves to be racially
discriminative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Afflicted Area in Mozambique Faces Shortage of Seeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Shortage of seeds is one of the
major difficulties faced by farmers in the southern Mozambican
province of Gaza, where the floods hit hardest in February this
year.
</P>
<P>
Chokwe District director of Agriculture and Rural Development
Custodio Macome said on Tuesday that the 2,500 kits of seeds and
tools distributed by the government and non-governmental
organizations could only cover about 60 percent of the needs.
</P>
<P>
"We are worried because the planting season is passing us by
and this may have serious consequences for people, whose
livelihood depends on agriculture," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Chokwe, floods destroyed about 26,000 hectares of crops,
including rice, maize, beans and cassava early this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Macome, the 700 or so commercial farmers in Chokwe
want the government to grant them loans at preferential interest
rates to restart their activity.
</P>
<P>
Some of these farmers will cultivate up to 10,000 hectares
each, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, administrator Albeto Langane of Chibuto district,
also in Gaza, said that his district is also running short of
seeds for the second season plantings.
</P>
<P>
In terms of livestock, Langane said that the district lost
about 4,000 heads of cattle to the floods -- a serious problem,
since most farmers use cattle for animal traction, and as a form
of wealth.
</P>
<P>
As for the resettlement of flood victims, Langane said that the
process is nearly completed and all the government-run
accommodation centers set up for the flood victims in the district
have now been dismantled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
