<HEADLINE> Coastal Resources Contribute Greatly to S. African Economy: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Coastal resources contribute
about 168 billion rand (about 24 billion U.S. dollars) annually to
the South African economy in the form of direct benefits, said
Deputy Minister of Environmental Affairs and Tourism Joyce
Mabudafhasi on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Cape Town on the launch of her department's White
Paper for Sustainable Coastal Development in South Africa,
Mabudafhasi said this figure represents about 35 percent of the
country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
"Indirect benefits, for example, erosion control and waste
management treatment, are worth a further 134 billion rand (about
19 billion U.S. dollars) a year," she said.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, the value of coastal ecosystems as a cornerstone
for development was not sufficiently acknowledged in
decision-making in South Africa," she said, noting that many
coastal regions that were marginalized under apartheid offer great
potential for future development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same function, South African Environmental
Affairs and Tourism Minister Valli Moosa said the white paper
signals a fundamental shift in thinking about the coast.
</P>
<P>
"It ushers in a new era for coastal management rooted in the
understanding that our coast is a national asset and belongs to
all the people of South Africa," Moosa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
