confirmed on Tuesday that it will partly finance the 21 new Boeing
737-800s to its short-haul fleet through the sale of its 15 Airbus
airplanes and equipment.
</P>
<P>
SAA's Vice President Richard Forson told South African Press
Association that Zurich-based Flightlease, a subsidiary of the
SwissAir Group which owns 20 percent of SAA, and its partner
company U.S.-based GATX Capital have agreed to buy the
above-mentioned airplanes.
</P>
<P>
Over 2 billion rand (about 290 million U.S. dollars) will be
raised through the sale of the Airbus airplanes and equipment,
Forson said.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed the 5.4 billion rand (about 770 million U.S.
dollars) order for the 21 aircraft in March, saying that SAA will
buy five of the aircraft directly from Boeing, with the remaining
16 to be leased from Flightlease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
