<HEADLINE> South Africa Eyes Regional Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The South African Tourism (SATOUR)
says it has embarked on an ambitious marketing strategy aimed at
promoting the 14 member countries of Southern African Development
Community (SADC) in the international tourism market.
</P>
<P>
SATOUR manager for Zimbabwe, Zambia and Malawi, Winston
Coercius, said currently, there were obstacles concerning regional
cooperation in the tourism sector which needed to be removed.
</P>
<P>
Coercius observed that obstacles in the region included visa
registration, which had become stringent to certain people.
</P>
<P>
He added that transporters such as buses, trains and planes
need to work hand in hand with organizations such as SATOUR in
order to provide information to would-be travellers.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a one-day workshop for SATOUR here on Tuesday,
Coercius said there was an immediate need for him to create
information points in Lusaka and Ndola, Copperbelt Province, in
order to establish close cooperation with each other in order to
effect a smooth flow of information.
</P>
<P>
He added that his organization intended to bring major car hire
companies and best hotels like Sun International for a workshop in
October this year so as to enhance their relationships with local
tourism operators in Zambia.
</P>
