<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels Continue to Violate Ceasefire: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Rebels in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) have been deliberately undermining the Lusaka
peace agreement and other initiatives meant to bring peace to the
DRC, according to a statement available here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Zimbabwe National Army spokesman Chancellor
Diye said this assessment was made by Ben Ncube, an official of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) allied forces
in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
He quoted Ncube as saying that the SADC allied forces had
crushed an ill- fated attempt by the rebel Movement for the
Liberation of Congo (MLC) to cut the main supply routes to the
town of Mbandaka and the areas around the Ubangi River.
</P>
<P>
According to Ncube, MLC rebels led by Pierre Bemba had been
marching southward since the beginning of May, encroaching and
occupying some government-controlled areas along the Ubangi River
which separates the Republic of the Congo and the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"The rebels have subsequently advanced southward from Imese, an
area they occupied at the time of signing the Kampala ceasefire
agreement in Uganda on April 14, 2000," Ncube said.
</P>
<P>
But the rebel advance along the Ubangi River was brought to a
halt on May 24 when allied forces dislodged and repulsed the
insurgents from Moboza, the official said, adding that heavily
armed rebels had ambushed a convoy of allied forces supply
vehicles en route to Moboza settlement.
</P>
<P>
Large quantities of arms recovered at Moboza indicated that the
rebels intended to advance southward and attack allied forces
position at Mbandaka, a town 800 kilometers northeast of Kinshasa
along the Congo River, Ncube said.
</P>
<P>
"The fall of Mbandaka would threaten Boende, Bokungu and Ikela
and thus giving an upper hand to the rebels," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ncube, there was relative calm elsewhere, although
there were some isolated incidents in the eastern part of the
country where other rebel groups had observed the peace
initiatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
