<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Market Short of Foreign Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Commercial Bank of Zimbabwe
Tuesday said the country's market will be still short of foreign
currency for the foreseeable future as exports remain depressed.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance reported a budget deficit of 21 billion
 Zimbabwean dollars (552 million U.S. dollars) in December 1999
which constituted 9.8 percent of gross domestic product and
exceeded a target of 7.5 percent, the bank said in its treasury
commentary.
</P>
<P>
The major cause of this large deficit has been attributed to
high inflation and interest rates and prospects of reducing the
budget deficit are out of reach unless the government cuts
expenditures dramatically, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"Continued borrowing by the government has partly contributed
to a high money supply growth to the tune of 40.5 percent in
February this year compared to a target of 10 percent," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Given the present situation, inflation is expected to remain
above 50 percent for a greater part of the year 2000," it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, tobacco, the country's single largest
foreign currency earner, sold in the past 20 days of the selling
season was 9.57 million kilograms and lower than the same period
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the low sales, the prices of flue cured tobacco were
 significantly lower than what the farmers obtained last year, the
bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank also said that despite a marginal appreciation in
common metal exchange, the gold price still remained suppressed as
volumes reduced.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is the third largest gold production country in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, trade is expected to be slow in the
coming months as demands wane off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
