<HEADLINE> Clinton, Arafat to Meet in Washington in Mid-June: Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will meet
with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on June 14 in the White
House, visiting U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the announcement at a press conference after two
hours of talks in the West Bank city of Ramallah with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Ramallah, Albright also announced that
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will resume their final-status
talks early next week near Washington. She said Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak has agreed to the resumption of talks.
</P>
<P>
She said that the two sides will have intensive discussions in a
bid to finalize a framework agreement, in preparation for a
permanent peace deal by September.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in the Middle East region from Moscow Monday in
an effort to bridge the gaps between Israel and the Palestinians to
thrash out the framework agreement on final-status issues including
Jerusalem, settlements, border, refugees and water.
</P>
<P>
She cautioned that both sides' demands will not be met fully,
but she said there is a golden opportunity to achieve better future
for the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, however, stressed again the need to implement the signed
agreements, especially sharm el Sheikh memorandum which is based on
the U.N. resolutions 242 and 338, in the same way Israel executed
resolution 425 to withdraw from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel complied with resolution 425 two decades after it was
adopted by pulling out all its troops from south Lebanon on early
May 24, ending its 22-year occupation there.
</P>
<P>
Albright has returned to Jerusalem where she started talks with
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy. She will then meet Israeli
President Ezer Weizman.
</P>
<P>
Barak met Albright in Jerusalem on Monday and is to meet her
again later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Albright will head to Cairo Wednesday to meet with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh.
</P>
</TEXT>
