<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE to Ban Mercy Killing, Cloning Human Being </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
will impose a ban on mercy killings by doctors and other medical
personnel under any circumstances, reported UAE's official news
agency Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under a draft federal law prepared by the Health Ministry, the
ban will apply even in cases in which patients suffer unbearable
pains and are under severe distress because of incurable diseases
and also when a patient himself wants it.
</P>
<P>
Any medical personnel committing "mercy killing" will be liable
to a 10-year-long imprisonment. But the switching off of artificial
respiratory equipment is not regarded by the draft as mercy
killing, in case three consultants agree that a patient is brain
dead.
</P>
<P>
It also bans cloning of human beings or carrying out any medical
research or experiments for the purpose of cloning humans.
Punishment for violation is 10 years imprisonment and a 20,000-
dirham (about 5,450 U.S. dollars) fine.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, its rulings and penalties will be
applied on medical staff in government and private institutions, as
well as specialists in herbal medicine, genetic engineering,
radiotherapy, laboratory tests, nutrition, medicines and medical
equipment, medical research and midwifery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Oil Pollution Threatens Mangroves in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Oil pollution in the Gulf is
threatening the growth of mangroves in the UAE waters, an ideal
habitat for a variety of fish, shrimps and other marine animals,
the UAE official news agency quoted a research study as saying
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The research, conducted by the Fisheries Department in the
Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries, showed that mangrove
seedlings will not germinate in even slightly oil-polluted soil.
Oil-soaked propagule (seeds) will not grow in unpolluted water
either.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), the United Arab Emirates (UAE) has
about 3,000 hectares of mangroves. A threat to the mangrove is a
threat to the sea animals living under its shade.
</P>
<P>
The mangrove is very luxuriant near the Umm Al Qaiwain Emirate
which is a very productive fishing ground, according to the
research.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf is always prone to oil pollution. The amount of oil
leaked into the Gulf waters during the 1991 Gulf War, as estimated
in November 1991, was between six and eight million barrels.
</P>
<P>
Among the other reasons for oil spillage are tanker collisions,
tanker wash-outs and a host of other illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
In view of its role in the development of fishery resources, the
Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries attached special attention on
the protection of the mangrove-grown areas and the cultivation of
mangroves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0059 </DOCNO>
