<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Refutes Muslim Leader's Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government refuted
Tuesday a top Muslim leader's accusation that the government
failed to fulfill the provisions of the peace agreement it signed
with the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora told reporters that 23.7
billion pesos (593 million U.S. dollars) worth of projects aimed
at transforming Mindanao into a food basket had been unveiled
during President Joseph Estrada's visit to the island three months
ago.
</P>
<P>
This is apart from the annual increased budgetary outlay for
the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM) from 3.07 billion
pesos (76.75 million dollars) during the period 1991-1995 to
almost 15 billion pesos (375 million dollars) during the period
1995-1999.
</P>
<P>
Aside from these socio-economic development projects, over 5,
000 MNLF members have already been integrated into the Armed
Forces of the Philippines, consisting of 160 officers and 4,960
enlisted personnel, Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
Another 1,000 MNLF cadres are now members of the Philippine
National Police, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zamora made the remarks in response to the charges raised by
ARMM Governor Nur Misuari before the 27th Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC) Foreign Ministers meeting held recently.
</P>
<P>
In that meeting, Misuari reportedly accused the government of
not fulfilling the provisions of the 1996 peace agreement with the
MNLF, citing the 26 years of a "supposedly fruitless search for
autonomy" to justify the need for the MNLF to revive its bid for "
self determination and independence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
