<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Meeting Calls for "Fair Basis" in Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries and economies
in the Asia-Pacific region should be integrated into the world
trading system on a "fair and equitable basis", participants of a
United Nations' regional forum said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's Ministerial Meeting of the 56th Commission
session of the U.N. Economic and Social Commission for Asia and
the Pacific (ESCAP) here, the delegates from 61 ESCAP members
discussed a wide range of issues related to globalization, and
agreed that the developing countries must be treated fairly in the
process of globalization.
</P>
<P>
While the developing countries must be allowed to develop at
their own pace, they said, strategic steps must be undertaken to
ensure that they can increase their knowledge level in order not
to be left behind in the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
Warning that "the developing countries would be further
marginalized if the widening gap between rich and poor nations
left unsolved," they call for the rich, developed countries to
take the lead in narrowing the divide.
</P>
<P>
For developing countries, they pointed out, that they should do
their best to adapt to the new environment of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Membership and effective participation in international trade
negotiations and organizations such as the World Trade
Organization can also be a good option for developing countries to
benefit from the globalization process and shielding themselves
against its negative impacts, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted, the trade negotiations among developing
and developed countries should be based on the principle of
fairness and equity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
