<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High School Graduates Eye Key Universities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- As the July 7 national college
entrance exam is approaching, information about the exam has
become a hot topic among students in China.
</P>
<P>
Over 100,000 students and their parents in Shanghai poured to
entrance exam consulting centers last weekend.
</P>
<P>
China's higher education institutions will continue to increase
college enrollments to three million.
</P>
<P>
For majority of high school graduates and their parents in
China today, it is no longer a dream any more to pursue higher
education. What concerns students most, is which university to go
to and what specialty to choose.
</P>
<P>
A teacher from Fudan Middle School in Shanghai said that most
of his students prefer a prestigious university rather than
selecting a specialty of their choice.
</P>
<P>
"Key universities have many advantages because their graduates
generally find jobs more easily, compared with graduates from
other universities," said the teacher.
</P>
<P>
However, parents emphasized that they want their children to "
get enough opportunities to foster their natural abilities".
</P>
<P>
Universities that have merged with other universities and
colleges have attracted many inquirers. After merging with Beijing
University, Beijing Medical University -- now the Medical College
of Beijing University -- has attracted a large number of students.
</P>
<P>
Chinese universities enrolled 2.7 million freshmen last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
