<HEADLINE> hke060659 --Sri Lanka Probes Accidental Bombing of Naval Gunboat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan air force Tuesday
were investigating an incident a day earlier when an Israeli-built
naval Dvora gunboat was bombed and destroyed accidentally by an
air force jet in the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Officials said they were trying to find out how the pilot
mistook the gunboat for a craft of Sea Tigers, the naval unit of
separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels.
</P>
<P>
They said 22 naval personnel were dead or unaccounted for in
Monday's clash after two Dvora patrol craft were hit in a mid-sea
battle off the Vetrilaikerni coast of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
One craft was rammed by Sea Tiger rebels but the second was
destroyed by the Sri Lankan air force which had been called in to
target rebel vessels in the area.
</P>
<P>
The military said they had destroyed at least four vessels of
Sea Tigers.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels said in a statement on Monday evening that they
lost 12 fighters in the fierce sea battle which lasted for several
hours.
</P>
<P>
The rebels claimed that they managed to damage at least two
other Dvora patrol craft.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan armed forces have been buying Israeli-built
modern weapons systems to boost their battle against LTTE rebels,
who have been fighting for a separate state for minority Tamils
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, government officials are preparing for a nationwide
celebration on Wednesday to boost the morale of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The ceremonies will be led by President Kumaratunga from her
official residence in Colombo. She is also expected to make a
statement to mark the event.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been battling to wrest control of the
Jaffna peninsula from the government troops since overrunning a
strategic base in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
