<HEADLINE> Estrada Orders Govt Agencies to Protect Sulu Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
has directed several government agencies to ensure the full and
effective implementation of existing and applicable fishing laws
and regulations to protect Sulu Sea and its tributaries.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Palace said Tuesday in a statement that
President Estrada also directed the agencies on Monday to
accelerate the development of the fishing industry in the area.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Abu Sayyaf, the extremist group holding 21 mostly
foreign hostages, called on the government to implement laws that
would prevent foreign fishing vessels from poaching in the Sulu
Sea and nearby waters.
</P>
<P>
Protecting the Sulu Sea was one of the three conditions set by
the Abu Sayyaf for the release of the hostages who were taken from
the resort island of Sipadan island in Malaysia on April 23.
</P>
<P>
The other two conditions, setting up an independent Muslim
state in Mindanao and the creation of a commission to protect
Filipino Muslims in Sabah, Malaysia, have been rejected by the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Presidential Palace, the president's order was
intended to bring lasting peace and development in Mindanao, which
he wants to transform into the country's food basket. 
</P>
</TEXT>
