<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 900 Million People Below Poverty Line in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Asian Development Bank (ADB) Vice
President Myoung-Ho Shin Tuesday said that an estimated total of
900 million people remain below the income poverty line in Asia,
noting the number accounts for two thirds of the poor population
in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
"A more resolute effort needs to be given to poverty reduction
so that fewer people would be vulnerable to future crises," Shin
said in his speech to the 2nd Asia Development Forum which opened
Tuesday morning with the participation of some 400 people from
across East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Shin drew attention to the social damage and the full human
costs wrought by the Asian economic crisis, emphasizing that the
poor continue to reel from the crisis, suffer the most and be the
slowest to recover.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis has highlighted Asia's persisting social challenge
made increasingly daunting by the number of poor people in the
region," the ADB official said, billing the renewed emphasis on
the problem of poverty as "one positive thing that has come out of
the crisis."
</P>
<P>
"The Asian crisis has also underscored the need for policy
reforms in social sectors, in addition to those in the banking and
corporate sectors," he added.
</P>
<P>
At the same gathering, Singapore Minister for Finance Richard
Hu also stressed the need to address the development gaps and
income disparities brought about by globalization and "New Economy.
"
</P>
<P>
"Globalization had brought about unprecedented prosperity but
also exacerbated income disparities within countries," he said,
noting that "the distribution of wealth and opportunities cannot
depend solely on the free market."
</P>
<P>
He said that Asian governments, the business community and
civil society need to work together to ensure that the less
prepared members of the population are given the necessary skills
to participate in the new knowledge economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
