<HEADLINE> OAS to Send Back Delegation to Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of American States
(OAS) adopted a plan Monday night to send back a delegation to
Peru, from which the OAS withdrew its monitors last month over
alleged election "irregularities."
</P>
<P>
Peruvian Foreign Minister Fernando de Trazegnies Granda
accepted the resolution, but denied any "electoral fraud."
</P>
<P>
He told the OAS general assembly that terrorists and inflation
were among major threats being faced by the South American country.
</P>
<P>
"That is why as Peruvian, we would like to be judged for what
we have already accomplished, not for what we have left to do to
reach a utopian ideal of democracy that can never be reached," he
said in a statement to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The OAS plan was adopted after debate in which some member
states expressed the fear that the organization is breaking with
the principle of non-intervention toward paternalism that revives
only memories of the Montroe Doctrine, a policy of U.S. domination
of the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministers from 34 member states are attending the 30th
OAS general assembly in Canada's southern Ontario town of Windsor,
where the meeting opened late Sunday and will end Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
