<HEADLINE> Rescue Work Done for Landslide-Locked River in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Work to unclog the Yigong River
blocked by a landslide came to an end today after 33 days of hard
work.
</P>
<P>
The landslide occurred on April 9 in the 7-km main course of
the Yigong River, closing off transportation routes to a nearby
factory and two townships. More than 4,000 Tibetan residents were
stranded.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the accident, the Communist Party of China Central
Committee, the State Council and the government of the Tibet
Autonomous Region sent rescue teams from the People's Liberation
army and armed police departments to create a canal for water
diversion. They worked day and night and completed a 850-meter-
long, 150-meter-wide and 24.1-meter-deep canal by June 4.
</P>
<P>
The canal is expected to be filled with water on Thursday. The
majority of rescue workers withdrew from the region today.
</P>
