<HEADLINE> Travel Craze Won't Harm Environment at Three Gorges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing travel blitz to the
Three Gorges, a scenic spot where China is building a gigantic
hydro-electric power project, is not likely to lead to a heavy
pollution problem in the dam zone, Chongqing Vice-Mayor Chen Jiwa
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has increased the number of garbage collectors at
ports along the Yangtze River and purchased more trash removal
equipment, Chen said at the Three Gorges Tourism Festival, which
opened today.
</P>
<P>
Billboards are covered with advertisements to remind visitors
of the importance of protecting the environment. Travel agencies
have also advised tourists against throwing rubbish into the river.
</P>
<P>
A drive to improve the ecological environment launched by five
provinces and cities on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River
will start next year. Teams of volunteers from all parts of the
country have arrived at Chongqing to aid the environmental
protection projects.  
