<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Westward Focus to Challenge Surveying and Mapping Depts. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The central government's decision
to develop west China has created both opportunities and
challenges for the country's surveying and mapping departments,
said the director of the State Bureau of Surveying and Mapping.
</P>
<P>
Surveying and mapping work done to date for west China's vast
area leaves much to be desired, SBSM Director Chen Bangzhu said.
Most maps of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region were made in the
1960s and 1970s, when the area lagged far behind the rest of the
country in development.
</P>
<P>
Chen told the People's Daily, China's leading newspaper, his
bureau will provide general surveying and mapping reference data
for the central government, including information on
infrastructure construction, environmental protection, and natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
Chen pointed out that western China's development is a
systematic and long-term task, which will make room for
innovations in the surveying and mapping work.
</P>
<P>
The bureau will cooperate with departments of water conservancy,
communications, civil affairs, and environment protection in
developing west China, said Chen, adding that his staff also will
supervise programs on the environment, global positioning system (
GPS) projects, and remote sensing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
