<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hails Its Contributions to Int'l Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- China's top environmental official
said here today China has made its due contributions to the
protection of the global environment as the largest developing
country in the world and a huge region facing numerous
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a forum on the thoughts of late Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping on foreign affairs, Xie Zhenhua, director of the State
Environmental Protection Administration, listed a number of
efforts China has made in international environmental cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China sponsored the ministerial meeting on the environment and
development in 1991, at which the Beijing Declaration was
published, the director said, adding the document had a great
impact on the United Nations Development and Environment
Conference in 1992, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, Li Peng, then premier of China, participated in the UN
conference, where he put forward five-point proposals on the
environment and development and took the lead in signing two
conventions on climate changes and biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
The director said China has signed a number of environment-
related conventions and participated in projects in cooperation
with other countries or international groups.
</P>
<P>
China also signed bilateral agreements or memos of
understanding on environmental cooperation with over 30 countries,
and 15 agreements on cooperation in maintaining nuclear safety and
radiation-free environments, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the international negotiations at global environmental
meetings, China has always abided by the principle that the
developed and developing countries have both common and different
responsibilities for global environmental problems, and opposed
hegemonies in environmental fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the excessive requirements developed countries
have asked developing countries to meet, China has made it clear
time and again that rich countries are obliged to take initiatives
in global environmental protection, and help developing countries
in protecting the global environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
China holds the view that from both historical and realistic
perspectives, developed countries are chiefly responsible for
today's environmental problems, while developing countries are the
victims, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Wang Guangya told those gathered
at today's discussion that rich countries have so far failed to
honor the commitments they made at the 1992 United Nations
Environment and Development Conference, including offering
financial support for developing countries to protect the
environment and provide environmental technology at preferential
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
