<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Government to Sell Holdings of Largest Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government plans to
sell its remaining 17.3 percent of Bank Hapoalim, the largest bank
in the country, on Tuesday in a public offering on the Tel Aviv
Stock Exchange, which is expected to raise as much as 2.6 billion
shekels (650 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government will sell 14.6 percent of the bank to the public
and institutional investors and 2.7 percent to the bank's
employees. The sale will be the largest public offering ever on the
local bourse.
</P>
<P>
The previous largest government offering took place in December
1998, when the government raised over 1.2 billion shekels (300
million dollars) from the sale of its 18.75-percent stake in
Israeli Chemicals on the TASE.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government collected bids for shares and warrants
from institutional investors in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"The road show was so successful that an extra day was necessary
to meet with interested investors", the Israeli daily The Jerusalem
Post quoted Shimon Gal, managing director of MI Holdings, as
saying. MI Holdings is a company in charge of selling state-
owned bank shares.
</P>
<P>
"If there is a 50/50 split between shares and warrants, the
offering will be considered successful," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government may prefer to sell all its holdings as shares,
but realizes it may get left with some warrants.
</P>
<P>
Gal is confident that investors with warrants will choose to
convert them to shares in 18 months due to the bank's dividend
policy, which assumes that the bank will continue to show high
profitability.
</P>
<P>
Bank Hapoalim posted favorable results in the first quarter of
2000, with an increase of 26.6 percent in net profit to 428 million
shekels (107 million dollars) and 16.9 percent net return on
equity.
</P>
<P>
The government still owns 43 percent of Bank Leumi and 53
percent of Israel Discount Bank, the other two largest banks in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Gal does not consider the privatization of the Discount and
Leumi as linked. Yet some analysts believe the government is
hesitant to sell off the relatively more attractive Leumi, fearing
it will limit the investors' interest in the less appealing
Discount.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are two consortia bidding for control of
Discount. The privatization of Discount is behind schedule,
according to a timetable originally set two years ago and Gal
believes a decision will be reached within the next few months.
</P>
<P>
The managing director also hopes to unveil privatization plans
for Leumi, the country's No. 2 bank, within two or three months. He
believes it must be a government priority to privatize banks,
particularly in the light of the increasing competition from
foreign banks entering the Israeli market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
