<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Syria to Meet on Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 6 (xinhua) -- Turkey and Syria are scheduled to
hold their sixth meeting on security and cooperation in Istanbul on
Tuesday, reported the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military said in a statement issued over the weekend
that the meeting will take place at Harbiye Military Museum and
Culture Center in the country's largest city.
</P>
<P>
Five previous meetings, two in Turkey and three in Syria, have
been held since the two countries signed an agreement in Adana,
south Turkey, on October 20, 1998, which determined a common
understanding on security and cooperation against the outlawed
Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Syria, which were at odds over security and water-
sharing issues for more than a decade, have recently taken steps to
improve their economic, social and military ties.
</P>
<P>
In another move indicating mutual desire for better ties, apart
from political contacts, the Turkish army football team is to have
a match with its Syrian army counterpart in Istanbul Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released by the Turkish General Staff,
the match, billed as football diplomacy, will be the first in the
two armies' history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
