<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Transport Minister Changes Mind on Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Transport Minister
Ling Liong Sik, who surprised the nation on May 22 by announcing
he will quit the Cabinet, Tuesday decided to stay on.
</P>
<P>
Ling, who is the president of Malaysian Chinese Association (
MCA), the largest Chinese-based party in Malaysia, made the
announcement of his change of mind in a prepared statement read
out to reporters at the MCA headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
Ling, who returned Monday night from a 10-day holiday in Perth
to think over his quit decision, said that he met Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Tuesday afternoon and has once again been advised
to stay on in his post.
</P>
<P>
The news conference called by Ling to announce his decision not
to quit, however, did not materialize as he declined to answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
MCA leaders, including Deputy President Lim Ah Lek, all four
vice presidents who were present, greeted Ling's announcement with
much cheer.
</P>
<P>
Ling said in the statement, "I am touched by the support and
encouragement of all parties calling on me to reconsider the
resignation from the cabinet post."
</P>
<P>
"I respect the wishes expressed by all parties especially MCA
members, community leaders, my supporters and friends. As such, I
would like to announce that I will continue to serve in the
government," Ling said.
</P>
<P>
After he made the sudden and unexpected announcement of his
intention to resign from his cabinet post last month, Mahathir
advised him to just keep his resignation letter and wanted him to
go on leave to think over his decision.
</P>
<P>
Ling's expressed intention to resign from his cabinet post had
created reactions among MCA leaders and party members at all
levels, leaders of Chinese organizations, Barisan Nasional (
National Front, of which MCA is a component) leaders and the
public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
