<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Aims to Becoming "eGovernment" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Tony Tan unveiled the eGovernment Action
Plan at the opening ceremony of CommunicAsia2000, Asia's largest
communications event, which opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that 1.5 billion Singapore dollars (870
million U.S.dollars) will be set aside to implement the
eGovernment vision over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The eGovernment vision is defined by Tan as one which members
of the public and businesses can reach and through which the
government wants to better serve the nation in the digital economy.
</P>
<P>
Besides the generous financing, the government has mapped out
five strategic thrusts to achieve the broad blueprint and its
desired outcomes.
</P>
<P>
These include pushing the envelope of electronic service
delivery, building new capability and new capacity, innovating
with infocomm technologies, anticipating to be proactive, sensing
to be responsive and developing thought leadership on eGovernment.
</P>
<P>
Six programs, that is, a knowledge-based workplace, electronic
service delivery, technology experimentation, adaptive and robust
infocomm infrastructure and infocomm education, have been
identified to support the five strategic thrusts.
</P>
<P>
"Governments the world over have a major role to play in
realizing the socio-economic potential and benefits of the
Internet economy for their industries and citizenry," Tan said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is prepared to challenge tried and
tested ways of doing things, even if these have been highly
successful in the past and are adequate for the present.
</P>
<P>
"The new economy demands that we adopt a 'creative destruction'
approach in our policies, regulations and work processes to keep
up with the rapid developments in the global economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore government took on a massive computerization
program in the 1980s, and by the 1990s almost all government
agencies had gone online.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
