<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Countries Urged to Grab Chances for Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Speakers at the ongoing Second
Asia Development Forum have urged Asian countries to seize the
current favorable opportunities to achieve economic growth and
bring about a new era of prosperity now that they have the
consensus that all Asian economies have emerged rather well from
the depth of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"This current state of relative economic stability is a window
of opportunity for Asian countries to prepare themselves to get
back on track for the next spurt of economic growth," Singapore
Minister for Finance Richard Hu told the gathering which opened
Tuesday morning with the participation of some 400 people from
across East Asia and the world.
</P>
<P>
The participants include officials from the World Bank and
members of the development community in East Asia including
leading policymakers, economists, development specialists,
academics, businesspeople and representatives of civil society.
</P>
<P>
"The worst may be over but it is no time for Asia to be
complacent. Reforms are far from complete," Richard Hu stressed
</P>
<P>
"The region will face increased competition for foreign
investments from other emerging markets like Latin America and
East Europe," he said, adding "the challenges of globalization and
the realities of the 'new economy' must be faced."
</P>
<P>
He urged Asian countries to better position themselves, to
create and seize the opportunities that will bring about a new era
of prosperity by writing out a prescription for sustainable
economic growth out of six lessons drawn from the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the opening of the forum, Vice President of
the Asian Development Bank Myoung-Ho Shin said recent
macroeconomic data on the crisis economies indicate that the
recovery has remarkably been more robust than anticipated and
Asian countries now have a better grasp of the policy measures
that need to be pursued in order to sustain the economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian crisis has underscored the need for policy reforms in
the social sectors in addition to those in the banking and
corporate sectors," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Vice President of the World Bank Institute Vinod Thomas also
stressed that need for East Asia to convert today's recovery into
a period of sustained, broadly shared growth and to make success
in transforming its business, public, and social institutions.
</P>
<P>
East Asia region provides an excellent laboratory for testing
the promise of a knowledge-led development strategy and they are
poised to share knowledge and seize emerging opportunities, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The forum, second of its kind, will last to Thursday. The first
one was held in the Philippines in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
