<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Inflation Rate Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Inflation rate has been on the
decrease in Mozambique in the past two months following a sharp
rise due to the devastating flood, local newspaper Noticias
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Finance Minister Luisa Diogo was quoted as saying
recently that the inflation in May was less than 1 percent,
plummeting from 7.2 percent in February after only 0.3 percent in
January.
</P>
<P>
Diogo attributed the inflation hike to the most serious flood
the country has seen in February and March.
</P>
<P>
She said the disaster had caused a sharp increase in the
government expenditure while the transportation of daily
necessities were blocked by the flood-ravaged roads, railway and
bridges.
</P>
<P>
The international community provided 50 million U.S. dollars
worth of relief aid to 2 million people affected by the flood, and
pledged 450 million dollars to support the country's
reconstruction in a donors conference in Rome last month.
</P>
<P>
Diogo attributed the fast drop of inflation rate to the
hospitable assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
