<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Offers to Host Second Earth Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has offered to
host the second Earth Summit which is set to take place in 2002,
Environmental Affairs and Tourism Minister Valli Moosa announced
in Cape Town on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the South African cabinet had decided to support a bid
to host the event and whether this is successful or not will be
known "in a month or two".
</P>
<P>
The first Earth Summit was held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, in
1992, where more than 100 heads of state gathered to address
urgent problems of environmental protection and socio-economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The assembled leaders also signed conventions on climate change
and biological diversity and adopted Agenda 21, a 300-page plan
for achieving sustainable development in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Moosa said many countries around the world believe South Africa
will be a suitable venue for the second Earth Summit.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the event, which is believed to be attended by
scores of heads of state and tens of thousands of delegates, will
have a large and lasting impact on environmental issues in the
Southern African region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
