<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Hails Ukrainian Decision to Close Chernobyl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Tuesday hailed
the Ukrainian decision to close down the nuclear power plant at
Chernobyl, 14 years after the world's worst nuclear disaster.
</P>
<P>
Gunnar Wiegand, a European Commission spokesman, described the
decision as "historic." He said the decision came 14 years after
the melt-down disaster and five years after the G-7 summit that
resulted in a memorandum concerning the closure of the nuclear
power plant.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine announced Monday that it is closing the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant on December 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission was delighted by the Ukrainian decision
and the timing was in line with Ukraine's long-standing commitment
with the G-7 and the European Union, said Commission President
Romano Prodi and External Commissioner Christopher Patten in a
joint written statement released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation EU, has
provided Ukraine with 100 million euro (94 million U.S. dollars)
as the Chernobyl shelter fund.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant is among the
conditions for the release of 92 million euro (86 million dollars)
macro-economic assistance from the EU.
</P>
<P>
The Prodi-Patten statement said that the Ukrainian decision
opened the way for rapid progress in the financial aid area,
including a substantial Euratom loan from the commission as part
of a global package involving the European Bank for Reconstruction
and Development and other donors.
</P>
<P>
Gunnar said the Euratom loan was in the amount of 1.5 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
