<HEADLINE> EU Condemns Solomon Islands' Rebels for Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Tuesday
condemned the coup in the Solomon Islands during which Prime
Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu has been taken hostage by the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
A European Commission spokesman said that the commission, the
executive body of the 15-nation bloc, said the commission "will
follow the situation on the islands closely."
</P>
<P>
The EC will consider a cut in the European aid to the island
country after the result caused by the coup becomes clear-cut, he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman added the EC would not cut off the aid
right away in a fear that the move could hurt the elected
government.
</P>
<P>
The EU has invested a total of 65 million euro (about 61
million U.S. dollars) in the island country, with 19 million euro
as financial aid.
</P>
<P>
A government official in the Solomon Islands said Tuesday that
Ulufa'alu had offered to resign following rising tension in the
country, so as to avert a civil war.
</P>
<P>
Gunfire was traded Tuesday near the airport between the ethnic
Malaita rebels and the Guadalcanal natives. 
</P>
