<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relocation Project Won't Force Residents out of Native Place: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
announced that about 90 percent of the residents to be relocated
from the reservoir area of the Three Gorges project need not go
far from their hometowns or travel a great distance to get to work.
</P>
<P>
Most of the residents will be able to live close to their
former home, said Wang Hongju, vice mayor of Chongqing
Municipality, which is responsible for resettling 85 percent of
the residents to be resettled from the reservoir area.
</P>
<P>
"Most old village names have been also used for the new
villages, and the only difference is that the villagers are living
in better-quality houses enjoying a better living environment,"
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
By launching the Three Gorges Project, China aims to build the
world's largest hydropower station. The project, planned to be
completed in 2009, calls for a total of 1.07 residents to be
relocated from the reservoir area.
</P>
<P>
Wang said about 100,000 of the relocated residents will leave
their homes in Chongqing for Sichuan Province in southwest China
and Shanghai, and these residents will be able to enjoy a much-
improved living standard there.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, only 140,000 residents will
be relocated to faraway places from their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
The relocation project has entered its second stage, with 230,
000 residents already moved to Chongqing alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
