<HEADLINE> World Venture Capital Eyeing China's Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from more than 50
world-famous venture capital firms, including Morgan Stanley and
the International Digital, have gathered here to gain a better
foothold in China's Internet development.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet in China is still in its primary stage, and we
expect it to have great potential. And the talent and market here
are also attractive to us," said Michelle Wu, President and CEO of
China Internet Group, Inc.
</P>
<P>
Wu told China Internet Venture 2000, which opened here today,
that her company has selected 24 of more than 200 development
programs for review.
</P>
<P>
The business plans involve infrastructure, E-commerce, consumer-
related E-business, and software application platforms, she said.
</P>
<P>
Executives of other venture investment companies said they are
interested in infrastructure and E-commerce among the more mature
enterprises and it is not advisable for people to rush to start
websites and business-to-consumer E-commerce.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 1,100 consumer-related websites,
compared with a little more 100 at the beginning last year. And
its Internet users have topped 10 million, according to latest
statistics.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce business volume is estimated to be 800 million yuan
by the end of this year, and will reach 10 billion by 2002.
</P>
