<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shas Threatens to Topple Israeli Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's coalition partner Shas party threatened Tuesday to topple
the government by voting in favor of a bill which asks for early
elections.
</P>
<P>
Shas Knesset (parliament) member Yair Perez said Tuesday that he
has been asked to mobilize the party's legislators to vote in favor
of the bill, which is expected to come up in the Knesset for a
preliminary reading on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill, prepared by opposition legislator Avigdor Lieberman,
is in pursuit of dissolving the Knesset and holding early
elections.
</P>
<P>
Up to now it is not certain whether Lieberman will ask the
Knesset to vote on his bill, and local political analysts said
Lieberman will pull his legislation if it is not guaranteed a
majority of 61 votes of the 120-member Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Barak and the Shas leadership took a rapid turn
for the worse on Monday. Responding to a Shas threat to vote in
favor of the bill if Shas' demand for fund allocations to its
educational system is not met, Barak ordered officials from the
Finance and Education Ministries to suspend their talks with Shas
over the funding.
</P>
<P>
Barak declared that he is not going to conduct negotiations that
are accompanied by Shas' threats, even if the threats are implicit.
</P>
<P>
Shas' education system is in deep debt due to its poor
management over the past few years. Education Minister Yossi Sarid
refused to allocate more funds to that system until it improves its
management and fires corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
Shas wants Barak to order Sarid to transfer millions of shekels
to its cash-strapped school system. And this dispute has been
dragging on for months without proper settlement.
</P>
<P>
Shas has 17 Knesset members. If it supports the new election
bill, Barak's coalition, already whittled down by defectors such as
the National Religious Party which disagrees with Barak's peace
policies, may have trouble for survival this time.
</P>
<P>
Shas chairman Eli Yishai is heading home from Geneva on Tuesday
to deal with the crisis. But Shas' spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia
Yosef, who has a final say over all party issues, has not yet
instructed the lawmakers how to vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
MANAMA -- Bahrain said that 50 percent of its fisheries lie in
the eastern and northeastern regions and that 5,457 fishermen out
of Bahrain's 6,930 fishermen work in the areas claimed by Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain's Fisheries and Marine Resources Department Manager
Hasim al-Kasir said such zones belonged to Bahrain since the old
times and the Bahraini fishermen have been fishing there for
thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish company Net Holding aims to raise its turnover
by 40 percent to 300 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Het Holding President Mehmet Ceritoglu said in Istanbul Monday
that his firm's essential purpose is to increase its profitability
through new investments.
</P>
<P>
The company will open a store in Prague and a hotel in Cyprus
this year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's state-run alcohol and tobacco enterprise
Tekel will soon launch a cigar joint venture with Cuban company
Catec.
</P>
<P>
As part of the deal, Tekel will give pre-financing loans to
Habanos S.A. within the framework of a five-year repayment plan.
Habanos S.A. will repay the loan in the form of tabacco.
</P>
<P>
Agreements regarding the project were signed in 1998. Tekel and
Catec will hold 50-50 stakes in the company, which will have
capital of three million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company will initially produce machine-made cigars and
Turkey will pay Cuba three percent of the royalties.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has got 8,000 tons of wheat from France to be
distributed among drought victims across the kingdom, Jordanian
officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The French wheat arrived in the southern Red Sea harbor of Aqaba
last weekend under the umbrella of the World Food Program (WFP) of
the United Nations, and will be distributed to drought victims
through the ministry of agriculture in Amman, the officials added.
</P>
<P>
The French wheat, valued at 1.35 million dollars, were part of
the 13,538 tons of wheat worth 4 million dollars promised by the
WFP in the year 2000 to the kingdom, which has been affected by a
severe regional drought since 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
