<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands PM Offers to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Solomon Islands' Prime Minister
Bartholomew Ulufa'alu Tuesday offered to resign as part of a deal
to end the country's crisis, the Australian Associated Press (AAP)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The AAP quoted Solomon Islands' Minister of State Alfred Sasako
as saying after an emergency cabinet meeting that Ulufa'alu "has
given an undertaking that if that was the price for the return of
peace in the Solomons, then, yes, he is willing to stand aside."
</P>
<P>
Ulufa'alu was escorted to the meeting at gunpoint by members of
the Malaita Eagle Force (MEF) which seized power in the capital
Honiara on Monday in a bid to oust him, the AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Sasako said, however, that the prime minister would not be
stepping down immediately and the cabinet caucus had accepted an
offer by Malaita Eagle leader Andrew Nori to drop his ultimatum
for Ulufa'alu's resignation by 5 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the caucus decided the matter would be settled at a
specially-convened parliamentary meeting on June 16 at which the
only item on the agenda would be the election of a new prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Sasako said Nori had withdrawn his ultimatum after being told
by European Union (EU) emissaries in Honiara that the EU would
cancel all aid to a Solomon Islands ruled by unconstitutional
means.
</P>
<P>
The EU provides 25 percent of the impoverished nation's budget.
</P>
<P>
Australia and New Zealand have urged Nori and the MEF to pursue
a change of prime minister by constitutional means only.
</P>
<P>
Sasako said Tuesday's development could offer the country a
legal and peaceful way out of its current dilemma.
</P>
<P>
He was hopeful the MEF would on Wednesday withdraw its gunmen
from the prime minister's residence and normal security would be
reinstated.
</P>
<P>
Ulufa'alu was kept overnight in what the militias called "
protective care" and escorted to Tuesday's meeting by armed MEF
officers.
</P>
<P>
But hopes for an outbreak of peace appeared remote earlier in
the day when 200 guerrilla fighters from the MEF and the rival
Isatabu Freedom Movement fought a three-hour gunbattle on the
fringe of Honiara's airport.
</P>
<P>
Four members of the MEF were wounded in the fighting, according
to unconfirmed reports on local radio.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 months, at least 50 people have been killed and
thousands made homeless in a dispute between the country's
indigenous Guadalcanal people and Malaitans, brought to the island
during World War II, over land ownership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
