<HEADLINE> S. Africa Concerned About By-Effect of Anti-AIDS Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- South African Health Minister
Manto Tshabalala-Msimang on Tuesday expressed concern about the
long-term effects of drugs used to prevent mother-to-child HIV
transmission.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who has been criticized for not making the drugs
available in state clinics, told the National Assembly that no one
would not want to protect unborn children from contracting the
AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
However, Tshabalala-Msimang also said there is a lack of
information on how the drugs affect unborn children over time.
</P>
<P>
She said she was looking forward to proposals that could
provide safe and affordable interventions that will help reduce
the risk of HIV transmission.
</P>
<P>
Tshabalala-Msimang said since President Thabo Mbeki last year
raised concerns about the toxicity of antiretrovirals, the South
African Medicines Control Council has concluded that the benefits
of AZT outweigh its risks.
</P>
<P>
However, the council further pointed to the fact that the
long-term effects of AZT on children has not been established.
</P>
<P>
A similar observation has also made by the manufacturers of the
drug in its package insert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
