<HEADLINE> DFB Chief Pledges to Prevent German Hooligans from Spoiling Euro 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- German Football Federation (DFB)
president Egidius Braun pledged on Tuesday that the federation
would do everything to prevent German hooligans from marring Euro
2000.
</P>
<P>
The tournament will be held from June 10 to July 2 in Belgium
and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"We must take all possible preventive measures to avoid any
kind of incident," Braun said after a meeting on security with
North Rhine-Westphalia state interior minister Fritz Behrens in
Duesseldorf. The state borders the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Behrens said those with a record of hooliganism would have to
report to local police and they would be barred from going to the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
Any of these people who did not report and attempted to cross
the border would be detained, he added. "We don't want to let a
few violent individuals ruin the reputation of Germany abroad. If
it's necessary we will detain the trouble-makers. Police have
enough cells," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch official said North Rhine-Westphalia police had paid
warning visits to 954 known hooligans in the area.
</P>
<P>
Police estimate the number of the most dangerous hooligans in
the state at about 1,100, with 40 of them having to report
regularly to police during the championships.
</P>
<P>
The tournament's security officials are concerned violence
might flare up when Germany and England, who were drawn in the
same group, meet on July 17 in Charleroi.
</P>
<P>
Both countries are known for soccer hooliganism and ironically
both are bidding to stage the 2006 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Four German hooligans were sentenced to jail terms last
November for beating a French policeman almost to death during the
1998 World Cup finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
