<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Court Drops Soeharto's Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- An Indonesian court Tuesday threw
out a multimillion defamation lawsuit filed by former president
Soeharto against Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
The decision was hailed by lawyer of the magazine Todung Mulya
Lubis.
</P>
<P>
" Today is happy day for the press because the judge has
demonstrated support of freedom of the press," Lubis told
reporters commenting on the court decision.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto last year lodged a libel lawsuit against Time over an
article published last year which alleged the 78-years old man had
amassed fortune illegally during his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
Time had reported that Soeharto and his family amassed a
fortune of around 15 billion U.S. dollars during his 32-year
authoritarian rule.
</P>
<P>
"A news article in connection with a presumption or a suspicion
of abuse of power by President Soeharto while he was in power can
be classified as a public necessity. Therefore it was not an act
of defamation," Sihol Sitompul, chief judge at the Central Jakarta
District Court, said in his verdict.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto has been under investigation for alleged corruption
practices during his 32 years in power. He had sought 183 trillion
rupiah (21.5 billion U.S. dollars) in damages over May 1999
article. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
