<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Cybertrading Set to Take off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Cybertrading in Malaysia is
set to take off and will account for 15 percent of all trade by
2003, according to a senior official of Investors Xchange Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The advent of cybertrading would inevitably lead to lower
brokerage fees and commission rates, which in turn would create a
virtuous cycle to drive more Malaysians to trade via the net,
Investors Xchange Managing Director Fahizul Khairi said.
</P>
<P>
With the country gearing up for greater financial
liberalization and the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange becoming a
world-class exchange, local brokerage firms would have to move in
step with the rest of the world by providing cybertrading
facilities, together with lower commission rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
Investors Xchange is Malaysia's first independent Internet
financial portal that enables internet trading with participating
equities and futures brokers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
