<HEADLINE> UN Launches $67m Emergency Appeal for Drought-hit Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Tuesday
launched a 6.7 million U.S. dollar emergency appeal for the
assistance of the drought-hit people in the war-ravaged
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Launching the appeal at a press briefing here, Acting U.N.
Coordinator for Afghanistan Syed Ahmed Farah said the present
drought response planned by the assistance community for
Afghanistan requires the implementation of projects totaling 67
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Farah said Afghanistan is currently in the grip of the worst
drought since 1971. The next chance for a normal crop from rain-
fed area will not be until 2001 because the vast majority of the
cultivated land produces only one crop per year.
</P>
<P>
While initial assessments showed southwestern Afghanistan to be
the worst affected area, it is now confirmed that the whole
country has been severely affected.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary result of the WFP/FAO crop assessment survey showed
that rain-fed crops in the north failed almost completely. The
Central Highlands are also seriously affected.
</P>
<P>
Due to a combination of war and deprivation, many of the Afghan
people were already highly vulnerable. The current drought, which
has lasted for half a year, has increased difficulties for a wide
segment of the population, Farah aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
