<HEADLINE> UNHCR to Provide Displaced Angolans with $11Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- UN Office of the High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) will provide the Angolan government with 11
million U.S. dollars, to aid the numerous war-displaced Angolans
living all around the country.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the Angolan ministry of assistance and social
integration Curry Duvall said this amount to will be used to buy
food and clothes, to build houses and temporary residences, and to
acquire other basic necessities for the displaced persons.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase of the program, those displaced people
living in the north region of the country, especially in the Uige
province, will be the first beneficiaries of the international
assistance since an office of the organization will soon be
established in the Uige city, capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, those displaced Angolans who had returned to their
homeland from Zambia and the Democratic Republic of the Congo will
also benefit from the aid, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In the year of 2001, namely the second phase of the UNHCR
program, the assistance will be expanded to all parts of the
southwest African country, which currently has some 3.7 million
displaced persons, accounting for 30 percent of the total
population. 
</P>
