<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Gov't Contributes Petrol Price Hike to Reliance on Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Information Minister Jerry
Gana Monday contributed the recent 50 percent petrol price hike
to the African largest oil producing country's awkward reliance on
foreign petrol imports.
</P>
<P>
He said in the country's capital Abuja that Nigeria imported 75
percent of the domestic consumed petrol products from foreign
countries, which left it no choice but to accept price offered by
the sellers, reported Nigerian newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To press down the price on domestic market, Nigerian government
had to spent billions of naira (100 naira equal one U. S. dollar
) in the first quarter alone this year on subsidizing fuel.
</P>
<P>
The breakdown of some of the country's refineries, due to years
of mismanagement, also contributed to the heavier reliance on the
imported fuel, thus to the petrol price hike, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He regretted the economic effects the increment may have on the
country' s average families, but appealed to them to understand
the rationale behind the hike.
</P>
<P>
With money saved from the subsidization, "I can assure you that
we can make this country better and be able to implement the 25
percent yearly increment for civil servants... without
retrenchments; even our railway systems and other serious economic
sectors will be better off," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Gana made the appeal at a time when large-scale protests were
seen throughout the country to protest the petrol price hike. The
Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC), the country's largest labor
organization, had also called upon its members and other workers
to begin a "seat at home" strike from Thursday June 8, if the
federal government did not rescind the increase petrol price.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian government on last Thursday rose the country's petrol
price by 50 percent to 30 naira from 20 (100 naira equals about
one U. S. dollar) per liter.
</P>
<P>
The decision had met with mixed reactions in the Africa's
largest oil producing country. People in the business sector
generally welcomed the move despite the costs added to their
operation, saying it is inevitable to reduce the large amount of
money spent on subsidizing for a low petrol price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
