<HEADLINE> Uganda Accuses Rwanda of Provocation in Kisangani, Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Uganda accused Rwanda Patriotic
Army (RPA) here Tuesday of conducting provocative action by
attacking on a vehicle of the Uganda People's Defence Forces
(UPDF) in Kisangani in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Uganda condemns in the strongest terms this
aimless and criminal provocation against an army committed to
withdrawal from Kisangani," said James Wapakabulo, chairman of
the committee on the region, at a press conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The UPDF vehicle, which was escorted by a vehicle of the United
Nations Observer Mission in Congo (MONUC), was fired at Monday
morning first by small arms and then by a shell which destroyed
it.
</P>
<P>
Later fighting broke out between UPDF and RPA in Kisangani, and
it continued this morning.
</P>
<P>
Wapakabulo said that the Ugandan government calls on the
Rwandan government to respect its commitment to the Lusaka
cease-fire Agreement, the Rwakitura Joint declaration and the
withdrawal plan.
</P>
<P>
"The Ugandan government also expresses its disappointment at
the U.N.'s failure to condemn up to now the irresponsible and
provocative actions committed by the RPA in the presence of U.N.
personnel," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wapakabulo said Uganda has proposed to MONUC that both sides
cease fire immediately, simultaneously withdraw troops of RPA and
UPDF from their current positions in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the withdrawal should be during the daytime
under the supervision of MONUC, not during the night.
</P>
<P>
"Uganda remains committed to Lusaka cease-fire Agreement and
the demilitarization of Kisangani plan as the only viable way
forward in resolving the crisis in the DRC," Wapakabulo said.
</P>
