<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich Countries' Huge Subsidy Weakens Poor Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The World Bank Chief Economist and Sector Director for Africa
Region Alan Gelb told a news conference here on Monday that the
developed world annual investment in agriculture is almost equal
to combined Africa's Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
"The World Bank would like to see a reverse of this set up
which has made African commodities lose their world market share
because of high prices," Gelb said, while launching a report
entitled "Can Africa Claim The 21st Century?"
</P>
<P>
He said that development of the agricultural sector in Africa
was also crippled by excessive taxation, however, about 80
percent of the taxation was siphoned to develop the
infrastructure in towns.
</P>
<P>
However, Gelb said, under the World Trade Organization rules,
industrial countries would be forced to withdraw completely
subsidizing the agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
"This move is likely to benefit developing countries," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The report was jointly published by the World Bank, the Africa
Development Bank, the United Nations Economic Commission for
Africa, the Global Coalition for Africa and the Africa Research
Consortium.
</P>
<P>
It challenges African governments to practice trade policies
which will encourage export oriented production.
</P>
<P>
Gelb's remarks come in wake of heated public debate on the
decision made by the Tanzania Government to abolish its farm
subsidies since early 1990s under pressure from donors.
</P>
<P>
The backbone of Tanzania's ailing economy, the agricultural
sector employs over 80 percent of Tanzanians and accounts for
over 75 percent of foreign currency earnings. However, the
sector cannot yet feed the Tanzanians throughout the year, though
the government promised to invest 75 million US dollars in the
sector in the next fiscal year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
