<HEADLINE> Tanzania Warns Incompetent Road Contractors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will not allow
incompetent and unscrupulous contractors to carry out government
projects in road maintenance and construction, a senior official
has warned.
</P>
<P>
The Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Works Solomon
Odunga, was quoted by local newspapers Tuesday, made the remarks
at a workshop here over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"I challenge all those contractors who have constantly been
doing unsatisfactory works in construction, maintenance and
rehabilitation of our roads, bridges, buildings and other public
structures to work more diligently," he said. "Otherwise, they
will find themselves out of business."
</P>
<P>
He said the government executive agency, the Tanzania National
Road Agency (TANROADS) responsible for developing and maintaining
roads on behalf of the government, would operate on commercial
principles.
</P>
<P>
TANROADS, established by the Executive Agencies Act, 1997, will
start operating next month.
</P>
<P>
Odung also challenged the Contractors Registration Board (CRB)
to strictly follow commercial principles in allocating contracts.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the CRB Chairman Malima Bundara said that more than 95
percent of construction work in Tanzania was being carried out by
foreign contractors.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania is too big to depend on foreign contractors," he
added. "The construction of schools, dispensaries, churches, rural
roads and water supply schemes are ideal projects for local
contractors."
</P>
<P>
Bundara called for deliberate measures from all stakeholders to
improve the situation of local contractors, who managed less than
30 percent of all projects only in terms of the value of the
construction work.
</P>
<P>
The two-day workshop, intended to review the status of various
strategies, attracted foreign and local contractors, clients,
members of the donor community, consultants, engineers, architects
and other professionals in the construction industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
