<HEADLINE> Russia's Putin Has Busy International Schedule for Next Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
will have a series of notable international meetings and foreign
trips this summer and autumn, which began with talks with U.S.
President Bill Clinton in Moscow and a working visit to Italy in
early June, a Kremlin official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
On his return from Italy Tuesday, Putin will meet in Moscow
with visiting Finnish President Tarja Halonen who visits to Russia
on June 6-7, Sergei Prikhodko, acting deputy chief of the Kremlin
staff, told the press.
</P>
<P>
On June 13-14, Putin will pay an official visit to Spain at the
invitation of King Juan Carlos I.
</P>
<P>
On June 15-16, Russian-German top-level consultations will be
held in Berlin with the participation of ministers.
</P>
<P>
June 16-17, Putin will make a working trip to Moldova.
</P>
<P>
Putin will receive his Kazakh counterpart, Nursultan Nazarbayev,
on June 18-19 and host a CIS (the Commonwealth of Independent
States) summit on July 20-21 when he will hold numerous bilateral
meetings.
</P>
<P>
In early July he will travel to the Tajik capital of Dushanbe
to attend a summit of the Shanghai Five group which includes
Russia, China, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan. The summit
will discuss regional security and promotion of cross-border
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A G-8 summit will be held in Okinawa, Japan, on July 20-23.
Prior to that, Putin may make a working visit to China, possibly
on July 18. The visit "is in the schedule," but the official date
has not been named yet.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement of Putin and Japanese prime minister
Yoshiro Mori at their recent meeting in Russia's city of St.
Petersburg, Putin will visit Japan and meet Mori at the end of
August or in the beginning of September.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian president's state visit to India is slated for
autumn," and the next Russian-EU summit is tentatively scheduled
for October in Paris, Prikhodko said. 
