<HEADLINE> China's Internet Development Hindered by Narrow Bandwidth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Chunjiang, Vice-Minister of
the Information Industry, today said that the most severe problem
China's Internet development facing is the narrow bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
He adressed the China Inet 2000 Beijing opened here today that
China's current basic Internet network can not meet the demand
with narrow bandwidth, high prices and unstable services.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country should introduce competition to the
industry and woo more investment to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, China's Internet has witnessed rapid
development. The number of Internet users have been estimated as
more than 10 million so far. The increasing Chinese websites and
new services, such as e-commerce and e-education are changing the
style of life of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Zhang admitted that some other problems, such as the hacker,
virus, and bad information in the Internet, were shared by other
countries and China.
</P>
<P>
At the four-day China Inet 2000 Beijing, experts will have
opportunities to discuss latest technological development and
services with some 100 keynote and technical speeches. 
