<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lao She Literary Prize Granted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- One of the bestsellers in China
last year, The Happy Life of Zhang Damin, was granted the Lao She
Literary Prize today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Another nine prize-winners, including novels, novelettes and
scenarios, are Dream on the Guanhe River by Ling Li, Ancient
Street by Liu Yuxin, How Far Is Forever by Tie Ning, Snuff Bottle
by Zhang Yonghe and Wang Baochun, Sima Xiangru by Guo Qihong, Year
After Year by An Zhanjun, Li Xiaolong and Li Xiaoming, Days
Without Lei Feng by Lei Xianhe, Kang Ning and Wang Xingdong,
Backbone by Li Jian and Luo Jin, Long Good Reputation by Li Jian
and Liu Baoyi, were also awarded the prize.
</P>
<P>
All authors, except Tie Ning who is a woman writer from Hebei
Province, are from Beijing, the hometown of the late literary
master Lao She.
</P>
<P>
The biennial Lao She Prize in Literature, set up by the Lao She
Art and Culture Foundation in 1999, should be presented to eminent
literary works which have "in-depth and meaningful text with a
distinct local flavor," according to a committee in charge of
judging writers' works.
</P>
<P>
Lao She, with a former name of Shu Qingchun, wrote to reflect
the real life of ordinary residents in Beijing. Literary critics
said that his pure, simple and expressive language came from the
working class and shines with the glory of realism.
</P>
<P>
His works include "Rickshaw Boy," "Camel Xiangzi" and a number
of plays including the famous "Teahouse" which was recently
performed again at the Capital Theater to packed houses.
</P>
<P>
The committee members expressed the wish that the prize will
become a major event on the literary calendar in China. Other
literary prizes in the country named after famous 20th century
writers include Lu Xun (1881-1936), Mao Dun (1896-1981) and Bing
Xin (1900-1999).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Terrorism in Turkey Against Iranian Interests: Iranian Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister
Mohammad Adeli denied reports that Tehran wants to destabilize
Turkey through a series of political killings amid allegations that
Iran plotted the bombing of a Pan-Am jet in 1988 which killed 270
people.
</P>
<P>
Adeli arrived in Turkey as Iranian President Mohammad Khatami's
special envoy to present Turkish President Ahmet Sezer with
Khatami's invitation to the Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO)
summit to be held in Tehran on June 10, Turkish Daily News reported
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said it is against Iranian interests that Turkey is embedded
in terrorism, adding that Tehran is disappointed over discussions
blaming Iran for destabilizing Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Seyyid Behbahani, an Iranian defector to Turkey, claimed in his
testimony that he had been an agent of the Iranian intelligence
organization, and some known terror actions which took place in
Turkey and other places had been masterminded by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Adeli strongly denied the allegations, saying that "Iran had no
relations with this person or other individuals or groups which
might have been involved in violence against Turkey or any other
country."
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran and Turkey should make utmost efforts to
remain calm and build mutual confidence which should prevail
between the different cultures and peoples of the world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an Iranian official said that following Israeli
withdrawal from southern Lebanon, Turkey had started to comply with
Israel's request to control Iranian flights over its national
airspace.
</P>
<P>
The official said that "some planes which carry humanitarian aid
to Syria are controlled by Turkey," expressing concerns over
growing ties between Israel and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
However, a recent statement by the Turkish Foreign Ministry said
that "Turkey has the right to control flights over its national
airspace. Turkey exercises this right whenever it chooses to."
</P>
