<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands PM Indicates to Stand Down: ABC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of the Solomon Islands'
parliamentary caucus on Tuesday has ended with Prime Minister
Bartholomew Ulufa'alu apparently indicating he would be prepared
to step down, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
His resignation has been one of the key demands made by the
militia which Monday put him under house arrest and seized weapons
and key installations in the capital, Honiara, the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) said.
</P>
<P>
The ABC quoted the Solomon Islands Minister of State Alfred
Sasako as saying the resignation is expected to take effect from
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"If that is the price, if his resignation is the price of peace
and the return to normalcy in the country then, yes, he is
prepared to do that," Sasako said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Australia's Foreign Affairs Minister Alexander
Downer has described the development as profoundly disturbing, the
ABC said.
</P>
<P>
Downer was responding shortly before he entered a meeting of
the Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group in London.
</P>
<P>
"My initial reaction is that he was put into a position at the
end of a barrel of a gun to resign, and that, of course, is what
is profoundly disturbing and regrettable," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
"Whether the prime minister resigned as a result of a vote of a
caucus meeting or a vote in the Parliament, of course, is a
domestic matter for another country but the circumstances which
led to his resignation are obviously profoundly disturbing," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, fighting broke out between armed members of the
opposing militia groups in the Solomon Islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
