<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Bad Loans Continue to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The non-performing loans (NPL) of
Thai financial sector are continuing to decrease, Thai official
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Finance Minister Pisit Lee-artham said in a report
Tuesday that by the end of April, the country's NPL has dropped to
1.95 trillion baht (50 billion U.S. dollars), or 36.5% of the
total loans, down 50 billion baht (1.3 billion dollars) from March.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Bad loans had peaked at 2.55 trillion baht (66
billion dollars), or 47.7% of the total loans, in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Thailand's NPLs are expected to decline
to 23% by the end of the year as banks are struggling to
reconstruct their debts.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Thailand, the central bank, even predicted the final
figure could be trimmed to only 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Thailand's Corporate Debt Restructuring Advisory
Committee said that since the number of debtors seeking
restructuring of their debts is still short of the targeted number
of 1.6 debtors per month, the pace of NPL restructuring is still
kept slow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sets IT Center for Hearing Impaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia launched Tuesday an
information technology (IT) center for the hearing impaired, the
first of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The center will give the hearing impaired a chance not to get
left behind in the IT race," Mohamed Sazali Shaari, president of
the Malaysian Hearing Impaired Federation, said through a sign
language interpreter at a press conference during the launching
here.
</P>
<P>
The disabled group, especially children, are also interested in
IT and the Internet, he said, adding the main obstacle faced by
the hearing impaired group is the lack of trainers who understand
sign language.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only 20 percent of those in the hearing impaired
group in Malaysia have an understanding of IT.
</P>
<P>
The center will provide IT training for hearing impaired pupils
from various special primary and secondary schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
