<HEADLINE> Nigerian Students Protest against Petrol Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian College students Monday
protested in Lagos and many other southeastern cities against the
recent petrol hike.
</P>
<P>
According to reports of major Nigerian newspapers, the
protesters demanded an immediate reversal of the prices and vowed
to resist any slash, which would result in even marginal
increases.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Adams Oshiomhole, president of Nigeria Labor
Congress (NLC), the country's largest labor organization
foreclosed any compromise on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Oshiomhole urged at an emergency press conference in Lagos that
 all Nigerian workers must ensure that "all the petrol stations
across the country are boycotted or shut down from operating
until prices are reverted to the old rates."
</P>
<P>
Most of the gas stations in Lagos remained shut on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Oshiomhole said the NLC was not to attend a meeting organized
on Tuesday by the federal government to discuss the hike. "We are
not going to meet with them until after our mass rally," said the
Labor leader.
</P>
<P>
The NLC last week called upon its members and other Nigerian
workers to begin a "seat at home" strike from Thursday June 8, if
the federal government did not rescind the increase petrol price.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian government on last Thursday rose the country's petrol
price by 50 percent to 30 naira from 20 (100 naira equals about
one U. S. dollar) per liter.
</P>
<P>
The decision had met with mixed reactions in the Africa's
largest oil producing country. People in the business sector
generally welcomed the move despite the costs added to their
operation, saying it is inevitable to reduce the large amount of
money spent on subsidizing for a low petrol price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
