<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urges Africa Ready to Face Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is worried that the
economic globalization could further widen the huge gap between
the rich nations and the poor, especially African countries, local
newspapers reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa told a conference here on Monday that
Africa should be nurtured to build the capacity of local
entrepreneurs to compete with foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
He said capacity building and the attraction of foreign
investment must go hand in hand to ensure the economies of
developing countries are not wiped out under the wave of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address to the two-day Conference on the New
Strategy for Denmark Development Assistance Policy, Mkapa said
that Tanzania that depends heavily on farm exports for most of its
hard currency earnings is very worried about rich countries'
subside on their agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
"Rich countries spend 300 billion U.S. dollars to subside and
protect their own farmers against foreign competition," he said.
"This figure is as large as Africa's total economic output."
</P>
<P>
"Clearly there is something wrong if milk from the European
Union is to sell cheaper in Dar es Salaam than milk from Dar es
Salaam," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa noted that developing countries need greater support from
their developed partners to make trade with outside world more
profitable.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tanzania, with about 80 percent of its people
living in rural areas, must increase production in agricultural
sector as well as boost non- agricultural sectors such as
small-scale industries and labor-intensive public works in its
efforts to reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa underscored the importance of cooperatives in promoting
and defending collective interests of the farmers, calling on the
donors to assist the revival of the organization.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperatives empower people by virtue of their individual
membership and strengthen unity among the farmers," he said
</P>
<P>
Mkapa stressed that donors and the developing countries must
learn to be more focused, targeted and realistic on what could be
done within what time frame work with the available domestic and
external confirmed resources.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the donor-established projects collapsed because they
did not have strategies to develop their sustainability," he said.
"One way to help redress the shortcoming is to have clear training
programs for local people to take over from expatriates in a bid
to ensure managerial and technical competence and sustainability."
</P>
<P>
The conference, organized by the government of Denmark, brought
together participants from Benin, Burkina Faso, Egypt, Eritrea,
Ghana, Kenya, Malawi, Zimbabwe, Mozambique, South Africa, Uganda,
Tanzania and Zambia as well as from international organization and
donors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
