<HEADLINE> McDonald Becomes Eighth Global Sponsor Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAUSANNE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- McDonald became the eighth
international corporate backer for the 2002 Winter Games in Salt
Lake City and 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens, Greece.
</P>
<P>
The four-year deal, worth between 50 million U.S. dollars and
60 million, represented another sign of restored corporate
confidence in the games following the bid scandals which engulfed
the Olympic movement last year, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee, which announced McDonald'
s renewal of its worldwide Olympic sponsorship, expects to sign up
at least two more sponsors for the 2001-2004 period and generate a
total of more than 600 million U.S. dollars from the program.
</P>
<P>
McDonald's, which will remain the exclusive retail food
service provider for the games, has been involved with the
Olympics since 1976 when it served as an official sponsor of the
Montreal Games.
</P>
<P>
The other announced sponsors for 2001-2004 are Coca-Cola,
Eastman Kodak, John Hancock, Sema Group, Time/Sports Illustrated,
Xerox and Visa.
</P>
<P>
They are partners in Top 5, the fifth edition of the global
sponsorship program created by the IOC in 1985. Kodak, Coke and
Sema have also signed up for the Top 6 program covering 2005-2008.
</P>
</TEXT>
