<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Speaking after meeting Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in
Jerusalem, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Monday
night that the "moment of truth is fast approaching" and each side
has to understand "it won't get 100 percent" of its demands.
</P>
<P>
Albright is expected to meet with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on Tuesday. She is also scheduled to visit Cairo on
Wednesday, where she is to meet with Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk
Shareh.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference with Barak Monday night,
Albright said "we are there ready to roll up our sleeves to help"
reach a permanent-status deal by the September 13 target date. She
added that this is "a historic time, and decisions have to be
made."
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The Shas coalition crisis, which has been latent for some
weeks, threatens to erupt Wednesday if an early election bill
sponsored by Knesset (parliament) member Avigdor Lieberman reaches
the Knesset for a vote.
</P>
<P>
Tension between Barak and the religious party's leadership took
a rapid turn for the worse Monday. Responding to a Shas threat to
vote against the government on Lieberman's measure if its demands
for allocations to its educational network are not met, Barak
ordered his professional teams to stop talks with Shas.
</P>
<P>
Barak declared that he isn't prepared to conduct negotiations
that are accompanied by Shas' threats, even if the threats are
implicit.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- An Israeli soldier was seriously wounded when a mine exploded
while he was on a mine-clearing mission along the border with
Lebanon Monday. The Israel Defense Forces is investigating the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Sappers have spent the past few weeks neutralizing mines along
the border to enable the construction of a new security fence.
Israel has undertaken to ensure that there is no encroachment on
Lebanese territory in order to comply with United Nations Security
Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. special envoy Terje Larsen is heading another
mission in the region to resolve outstanding points over the
precise location of what the U.N. refers to as the "withdrawal
line."
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources hope that the stumbling blocks will be
overcome in a few days, and the U.N will then be able to complete
the process of verifying Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The Tel Aviv Magistrate's Court meted prison terms to five
men convicted of negligence offenses in a bridge collapse incident
at the opening ceremony of the 1997 Maccabian Games, or the Jewish
Olympic.
</P>
<P>
Four members of the Australian contingent to the games were
killed in the Ramat Gan tragedy, and 69 were injured.
</P>
<P>
Judges distinguished between the defendants' level of complicity
in the affair, and handed prison terms of varying lengths from nine
months to 21 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
