<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's monthly tax revenues hit an all-time high
of 13.02 billion shekels (3.25 billion U.S. dollars) in May, up 18.
8 percent over the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months of the year, tax revenues totaled 62.
15 billion shekels (15.54 billion dollars), 20.3 percent over the
same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Treasury officials warned, however, that though the increase
clearly points to economic growth, it is not necessarily an
indication of the magnitude of the boom.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israel Export Institute has set up a
computerized database of investors, managers and marketing
personnel for software companies, in an effort to help them
penetrate overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
Israeli software exports totalled 2.2 billion dollars in 1999,
which constituted 45 percent of the country's total service
exports.
</P>
<P>
The investment database comprises 200 investment institutions in
the United States and western Europe, including venture capital
funds and investment banks.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Union Bank of Israel will hold its initial public
offering on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange on Wednesday, with the goal
of raising at least 169 million shekels (62.2 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of this sum, 64 million shekels (16 million dollars) will come
from the sale of shares to bank employees.
</P>
<P>
The bank will also issue options which, if fully exercised, will
bring in an additional 140 million shekels (35 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's leading maritime company Arkas is building
the country's largest container port in the eastern Marmara town of
Gebze.
</P>
<P>
The company said in its monthly publication that the first unit
of the port will become operational in 2001.
</P>
<P>
It added that ships of any size could dock at the 1,300 meter-
long wharf with a water depth of 16.5 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
