<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Unhappy With Annan's Reference on Missing Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A parliamentary delegation of Cyprus
will travel to New York to meet United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan to discuss the missing persons issue of the island,
local media reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his recent report on renewing the six-month mandate of the
UNFICYP's (U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus), Annan said he will
not appoint another U.N. member to the Committee for Missing
Persons (CMP), composed of representatives also from the two
communities of Cyprus, until the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides
show a "genuine committment to reaching a consensus on the issue of
missing persons."
</P>
<P>
Jean-Pierre Ritter, the former U.N.-appointed member of the
tripartite CMP, died in January.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou said such a
point of view took no account of the agreement on the issue of
missing persons reached between President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
In July 1997, Clerides and Denktash agreed to exchange
information on the location of graves, but efforts appear to have
been snagged as the Greek Cypriots accused the Turkish Cypriot side
of non-cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"This reference is not fair to our side and completely overlooks
the July 1997 agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou also accused that the reference put on an equal
footing the legal armed forces of the Republic of Cyprus and the
Turkish army, which has been occupying the Turkish Cypriots-
populated northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Parliament Speaker Spyros Kyprianou also said "Annan's
position is unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,619 Greek Cypriots were listed as missing persons
soon after the 1974 incident.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side refused to return to talks on the
missing persons, saying the Greek Cypriot side included people
killed in the coup on the list of missing persons.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side unilaterally started last summer a
process of exhumation and identification of remains of the dead and
missing persons in the 1974 war from two local cemeteries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
