<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Central Bank Governor Urged to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Speaker of the Indonesia's
House of Representatives (DPR) Muhaimin Iskandar here Tuesday
asked Governor of Bank Indonesia (the central bank) Syahril
Sabirin to resign from his post following his alleged involvement
in a bank scandal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Iskandar said," I think it would be
better if Syahril Sabirin resign from his position as governor (of
the central bank). Because in this case he was declared as a
suspect by the Attorney General Office."
</P>
<P>
However, Speaker of the DPR Akbar Tandjung insisted that, "the
principle of presumption of innocent have to be erected in
handling the Bank Bali case and let the court decides. And it will
better for us to wait."
</P>
<P>
He urged Sabirin to remain in his post "until the court finds
him guilty in the scandal."
</P>
<P>
Sabirin was named on Monday as suspect in the country's Bank
Bali scandal for allegedly violating the central bank's prudential
principle in its policy to reimburse interbank loans guaranteed by
the government.
</P>
<P>
The scandal revolves around Bank Indonesia's reimbursement of
904 billion rupiah (129 million U.S. dollars) in defaulted loans
to other banks. There is a suspicion that a large portion of the
money went to help bankroll then president B.J. Habibie's
renomination bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
