<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Claims Recovering Tesseney Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Eritrean troops have recaptured
the western town of Tesseney after a day-long battle with
Ethiopian army, according to a news release from the Eritrean
Foreign Ministry on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian troops consisting of one division and two
brigades were totally routed at around 9:00 p.m. on Monday, the
release claimed.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea accused the Ethiopian army of demolishing all major
public and commercial facilities as well as private homes in
Barentu, east of Tesseney.
</P>
<P>
The news release said that Ethiopia continued to reject the
call by the Organization of African Unity (OAU) to withdraw fully
from western Eritrea and still occupy a number of Eritrean towns
in the agriculturally rich part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea claimed that Ethiopia's design is aimed at "delaying
and preventing the early return of the displaced people so as to
disrupt agricultural production during the critical month of June
when the rains are due".
</P>
<P>
Over 60 percent of Eritrea's agricultural production comes from
the western part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia declared on May 31 that the war was over. The
announcement was made while it claimed to have recovered all
occupied territories from Eritrea, and attained all its military
objects.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are now involved in a new round of indirect
peace talks brokered by the OAU in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of fighting in a two-year-old border conflict
between the two Horn of Africa neighbors erupted on May 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EX-AUM Member Given Life Term For Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Tokyo District Court on Tuesday
sentenced former AUM Shinrikyo member Yoshihiro Inoue to life in
prison for murder and other crimes related to 1995 sarin nerve gas
attack on the Tokyo subway system that killed 12 people and
injured thousands, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
Inoue, 30, was one of the closest aides to AUM founder Shoko
Asahara. In addition to the murder of the sarin gas attack victims,
he was found guilty of taking part in other cases of murder and
kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
The public prosecutors have demanded the death sentence for
Inoue, but the call was rejected by the presiding judge on the
ground that the defendant did not play an active role in the
crimes, such as releasing sarin in the subway trains.
</P>
<P>
Koichi Ueda, a senior official at the Tokyo District Public
Prosecutors Office, said he did not expect the ruling to be life
imprisonment for such serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
Ueda said he plans to appeal the ruling after discussing the
case with the Tokyo High Public Prosecutors Office.
</P>
<P>
The court also rejected a defense plea that Inoue followed
Asahara's orders under "mind control", therefore, he was not fully
responsible for his actions.
</P>
<P>
A 29-year-old woman whose father was killed in the sarin attack
was quoted by Kyodo as saying, "It was a completely unexpected
ruling. I'm confused, to be honest."
</P>
<P>
Takeshi Tsuchimoto, a professor of the Penal Code at Teikyo
University, told the Japanese news agency that the court should
have handed down the death penalty, because Inoue planned,
prepared and carried out so many lethal crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
