<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Flame Burns Across Wellington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Olympic flame on Tuesday
touched down in Wellington, Capital of New Zealand, for the first
time in its 64-year history.
</P>
<P>
Around 100 runners from Wellington and the lower half of New
Zealand's North Island took part in the Olympic torch relay
through the streets of the capital, the National Museum of New
Zealand and the Parliament Building as it passed through New
Zealand on its way to the 2000 Sydney Olympics. It finished at
Civic Square, where an entertainment including music and
performances was organized.
</P>
<P>
Among the flame carriers were New Zealand Governor-General Sir
Michael Hardie Boys; Prime Minister Helen Clark; Sports Minister
Trevor Mallard; New Zealand Olympic Committee's patron, 102-year-
old Irene Emery; film-maker Peter Jackson; former swimming star
Rebecca Perrott; wheelchair rugby player Sholto Taylor; disabled
runner Timothy Prendergast; equestrian Sally Clark and cricketer
Gavin Larsen.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Olympic flame arrived in New Zealand from Tonga
and passed through Queentown, a world-famous scenic city, and
Christchurch, the biggest city on New Zealand's South Island. It
is due to go to Rotorua and Auckland on the upper half of the
North Island Wednesday, before leaving New Zealand for Australia
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic flame was lit at Olympia, Greece, on May 10. The
torch ceremony dated from the Berlin Olympiad in 1936. 
</P>
</TEXT>
