<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Refutes False Claim Over Lockerbie Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Intelligence Minister Ali
Yunesi has refuted a claim by the alleged defector Ahmad Behbahani
that Iran was behind the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet over
Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Denying any links with Behabahani, the minister said that since
the establishment of the Iranian Intelligence Ministry, no person
named Ahmad Behbahani has worked with the ministry, the Islamic
Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The United States' Columbia Broadcasting System (CBS) disclosed
on Sunday that Behbahani, who claimed himself former head of the
ministry's department in charge of foreign terrorism activities,
said Iran planned and carried out the 1988 bombing.
</P>
<P>
Behbahani, living in a foreign asylum-seeker camp in Turkey,
said that he had been responsible for all "terrorist" operations
carried out by the Iranian government beyond its borders until he
had crossed the border to Turkey four months ago following a rift
with his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
He said that a group of Libyans received 90 days of training in
Iran to carry out the bombing after he persuaded Ahmad Jibril, who
heads a Syrian-backed armed group, the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, into accepting the plan.
</P>
<P>
In response to Behbahani's claim, Yunesi told IRNA on Monday
that those Iranians who wish to be granted asylum in the Western
countries usually try to achieve their aims through baseless
statements or slanders against Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said the "contradictory" remarks of Behbahani proves the
falseness of his claims since he claimed to be imprisoned in Iran
in 1998 while claiming to be a top official with the Iranian
Intelligence Ministry in the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
