<HEADLINE> Wahid Optimistic Over Indonesia's Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid said here Tuesday he was optimistic that the Indonesia's
unity will remain intact.
</P>
<P>
"I have never worried about disintegration (threats) in this
country," Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
With his new statement, it seems that Wahid also played down on
what is happening in the resource-rich province of Papua recently.
</P>
<P>
"I don't worry at all. And I am sure that the Indonesia's unity
will remain intact," Wahid said, referring to what is happening in
the province.
</P>
<P>
He also said that based on a historical point of view Papua
province has a strong commitment for integration with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Papua National Congress declared on Sunday that the
province will be no longer a part of the unitary state of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
But earlier the president vowed to take some measures against
all activities aimed at declaring an independent Papua, saying
that the government would also not recognize the results of the
congress as its organization was not in line with the agreement
reached by the government and the congress organizing committee.
</P>
