<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stlead: Death Toll Reaches 103 in Earthquake in  Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in a powerful
earthquake in Bengkulu on Indonesia's Sumatra island rose to 103
and leaving 500 injured on Tuesday noon, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the death toll would likely continue to
rise as they had not been able to contact the worst-hit areas,
including Enggano island which lies close to the earthquake's
epicenter and is home to 1,500 people.
</P>
<P>
Rescue teams were trying to push into remote parts of Bengkulu
province, but were hampered by bad weather, severed communications
and the closure of the region's airport.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted a government emergency task force as saying
that 64 bodies had been recovered from rubble in Bengkulu town.
The rest were killed in other parts.
</P>
<P>
The Antara News Agency said more than 500 people had been
injured, half of them seriously. Doctors in the provincial capital
of Bengkulu were struggling with a shortage of beds, medicine and
blood and were treating victims in hospital parking lots.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, Acting Coordinating Minister for Political and
Security Affairs Surjadi Sudirdja said Indonesia needed
international assistance.
</P>
<P>
"In this situation we expect help. The situation now is worse.
Because the airport cannot be used, it is hampering the arrival of
aid. So aid will be delivered by sea and land. Maybe we will use
military helicopters to drop food," the minister told reporters
after meeting President Abdurrahman Wahid.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that two Indonesian Navy ships were bringing
emergency supplies. Rescue personnel were being deployed from
other parts of Indonesia, and some foreign countries had offered
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The strong earthquake measuring 7.9 on the Richter Scale hit
Bengkulu on Sunday mid-night when most residents were sleeping.
The epicenter of the quake was located 112 kilometers from
Bengkulu. More than 300 aftershocks have been recorded since the
tumble hit.
</P>
<P>
The tumble was also felt in the coastal areas of West Sumatra,
South Sumatra, Lampung and West Java, but there were no immediate
reports of damage or casualties there.
</P>
<P>
Expert from the Bandung Institute of Technology Sikgit Sukmono
said Sunday's quake resulted from a movement in the Indo-Australia
tectonic plate.
</P>
<P>
It was the second major earthquake to jolt Indonesia within
less than two months. A quake measuring 5.2 on Richter Scale and a
subsequent tsunami hit Luwuk-Banggai island in Central Sulawesi
earlier last month, leaving 45 people dead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Gov't Accuses Rebels of Forcibly  Conscripting Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government Tuesday
accused Tamil Tiger rebels of forcibly conscripting civilians in
northern Jaffna peninsula under the cover of a one-day unilateral
cease-fire late last month.
</P>
<P>
"A large number of males and females including school children
from Kaithady and Ariyalai areas who were forced to move into
Wanni ... have been conscripted ... and are presently undergoing
military training in the Wanni," said a government statement.
</P>
<P>
The accusation came as the government claimed that over 1,000
rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have been killed
and twice that number have been wounded in the recent battles in
Jaffna where the rebels are experiencing an acute manpower
shortage.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, fighting for a separate state for minority
Tamils in Sri Lanka's northern and eastern parts since 1983, have
been engaged in a ferocious assault over the past two months in a
bid to retake their former stronghold of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
However, the rebel offensive seem to be dying down as only
sporadic fighting has been reported for the past week.
</P>
<P>
Military spokesman Palitha Fernando said LTTE transmissions had
revealed the names of 650 rebels killed in various clashes in the
recent past.
</P>
<P>
He said the morale of the government troops in Jaffna is high
as the government has rushed modern weaponry systems and
reinforcements to beef up the defenses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government accused LTTE rebels of blocking the
movement of civilians under its control in the Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The government statement said the LTTE rebels have refused to
allow civilians to cross over to the government-controlled areas
in Jaffna despite arrangements made by the government to open an
entry point in the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
It said the rebels instead are forcing civilians to move into
the northern jungle region of Wanni. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
