<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Bank Grants Loan to Kenya's Power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Investment Bank has
granted a loan of 41 million euros (about 38.7 million U.S.
dollars) to Kenya for the construction of sub-station and
transmission line of the Olkaria II power station, local
newspapers reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary of the Energy Ministry Mwanyengela Ngali
disclosed it Monday when he led the European Investment Bank
officials on a tour of the Olkaria Geothermal Power Project near
Naivasha in central Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Ngali said the European bank also financed the third unit of
the existing Olkaria I Power Station built in 1985 at a cost of
144 million shillings (around two million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He noted that geological studies indicate that Kenya has a
geothermal potential of over 2,000 megawatts, equal to the hydro
potential of the River Nile in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to Kenya's bilateral partners to assist in the
exploitation of the resources, saying this could help reduce over
dependence on hydropower generation in the country.
</P>
<P>
kenya began power rationing last September due to a two-year
drought leading to the fast drop of the water levels of major
reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government introduced a 12-hour power rationing
schedule nationwide until the onset of the short rains in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
