<HEADLINE> Share Prices Move Lower in Tokyo on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices moved lower in Tokyo
Tuesday on profit-taking following gains during the previous four
trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped 31.71 points, or 0.18
percent, from Monday's close to end at 17,170.08.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 6.78 points or 0.42 percent to 1,588.66.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 716.40 million
shares from Monday's 666.76 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Materials was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Institutional investors showed a strong interest in bargain-
hunting whenever share prices fell, lifting the Nikkei to plus
territory at one stage during the day, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Brokerage houses succumbed to selling following their recent
gains, while real-estate firms, banks and nonlife insurers also
saw declines.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information and technology issues were mixed
following Monday's gains on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Low- and medium-priced issues drew active buying, traders said,
adding that paper manufacturers, glassmakers and wholesalers were
among gainers.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers with 684 to 557, as well as 151 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
