<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Link With Alleged Defector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Intelligence Minister Ali
Yunesi has denied any links between his ministry and the alleged
defector Ahmad Behbahani, who claimed that Iran was behind the 1998
bombing of a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of the Iranian Intelligence Ministry, no
person named Ahmad Behbahani has worked with the ministry, the
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) on Tuesday quoted him as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The United States CBS television broadcast on Sunday that
Behbahani, who claimed himself former head of the ministry's
department in charge of foreign terrorism activities, said Iran
planned and carried out the 1998 bombing which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Behbahani, living in a foreign asylum-seeker camp in Turkey,
said that he had been responsible for all "terrorist" operations
carried out by the Iranian government beyond its borders until he
had crossed the border to Turkey four months ago following a rift
with his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
He said that a group of Libyans received 90 days of training in
Iran to carry out the bombing after he persuaded Ahmad Jibril, who
heads a Syrian-backed armed group, the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, into accepting the plan.
</P>
<P>
In response to Behbahani's claim, Yunesi told IRNA on Monday
that those Iranians who wish to be granted asylum in the Western
countries are usually trying to achieve their aims through baseless
statements or slanders against Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said the "contradictory" remarks of Behbahani proves the
falseness of his claims since he claims to have been imprisoned in
Iran in 1998 while claiming to be a top official with the Iranian
Intelligence Ministry in the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
