<HEADLINE> DPRK Intends to Set Up Diplomatic Ties with NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) has raised a proposal on the establishment of
diplomatic relations between the DPRK and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK's proposal was contained in a press release issued
Monday by the DPRK Embassy in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The release, which was circulated Tuesday at the New Zealand
Parliament, said the DPRK is "fully prepared to begin diplomatic
contacts with New Zealand, if Wellington agrees to the proposal on
opening diplomatic ties."
</P>
<P>
The DPRK's proposal follows the recent statement by New Zealand
Prime Minister Helen Clark in favor of such a relationship between
the two countries. The prime minister told the New Zealand
Institute of International Affairs in Wellington on May 26 that
her country would probably follow Australia's example and
eventually establish diplomatic links with the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The release said DPRK welcomes Clark's statement as "an
important indication of New Zealand's foreign policy development,
being consistent with the recent movement in Asia-Pacific that
further promotes confidence-building process and cooperation in
the region."
</P>
<P>
"The DPRK is of the view that establishment of diplomatic
relations will make a significant contribution to greater peace
and prosperity in the Asia-Pacific, to which the two countries
belong,"it said. 
</P>
