<HEADLINE> Political Violence Decreases in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- With three weeks to go before
Zimbabwean parliamentary elections, police Monday said they are
winning the fight against political violence, the daily Herald
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There has been a notable decrease in the number of political
violence incidents reported countrywide in the past week, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 people were killed, 450 others arrested and property
worth millions of U.S. dollars destroyed since the countrywide
outbreak of political violence in February.
</P>
<P>
In an interview Monday, police spokesman Chief Superintendent
Wayne Bvudzijena said that though there were some cases still
being reported the number of incidents was on the decrease.
</P>
<P>
He cited last weekend's peaceful filing of election candidates
saying people have now realized that the outcome of the elections
will be decided by the ballot and not violence.
</P>
<P>
He said police force will continue to deploy its officers to
all parts of the country ahead of the elections.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe will hold the fifth parliamentary elections on June 24
and 25.  
</P>
