<HEADLINE> Kenya Vows to Punish Crimes of Environment Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Minister for Environment
has warned that those found polluting the environment will be
prosecuted since the environmental law is in force.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times newspaper quoted Francis Nyenze on Tuesday as
saying that his ministry will crack down on companies without
necessary facilities to treat wastes.
</P>
<P>
Nyenze said that some companies had dumped sewage into rivers,
causing untold suffering to human and marine life and a big chunk
of the health budget to treat water-borne diseases.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the celebrations of the World Environment Day in
the Kenyan town of Thika, he also urged the Castle Brewing Company
(South Africa) in the town to speed up the construction of their
treatment plant in order to improve the ecosystem of the area.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the current drought that is ravaging
the country can partly be blamed on the deforestation and appealed
to Kenyans to plant trees to offset desertification.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government will not condone people who destroy
forests, especially in the catchment areas. 
