<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildfires Still Burning in Four U.S. States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Large wildfires were still
burning Monday in three Western states and one Eastern state of
the United States, according to reports by local officials.
</P>
<P>
Of the seven currently active wildfires across the country, the
largest is in northern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
One blaze, in the Sangre de Cristo Mountains, New Mexico, has
forced hundreds of people to evacuate from the pine forest east of
Santa Fe. The week-long fire had increased to 28,283 acres by
Sunday night, the federal government's National Interagency Fire
Center reported on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
South of Los Alamos, also in New Mexico, the Cerros Grande fire
at Bandelier National Monument should be contained by Tuesday,
officials said. As of Sunday night, it had burned 47,650 acres.
</P>
<P>
In Nevada, a fire in the Humbolt-Toiyabe National Forest, 10
miles (16 kilometers) east of Pahrump, had burned 3,500 acres as
of Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
In Arizona, a fire in Kaibab National Forest, 25 miles (40
kilometers) northwest of Flagstaff, had burned 12,300 acres as of
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Federal officials are considering closing thousands of acres of
national forest land in Arizona to reduce the chance of a
disastrous fire season.
</P>
<P>
Florida has been the focus where fires were still burning on
state land in three separate areas: northeast of Gainesville,
north of Tampa and in Sarasota County. No containment dates have
been forecast.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, more than 41,000 wildfires throughout the
United States have scorched more than 1 million acres, according
to the federal government's National Interagency Fire Center.
</P>
