<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dominance of E-Commerce Expected to End in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dominance of Internet
commerce is expected to end next year as a result of increased
international online buyers and popularity of business-to-business
Web transactions, the International Data Corporation (IDC) said
Monday in a report.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. share of worldwide Internet commerce will plunge from
62 percent in 1999 to 48 percent in 2001, according to the report
by the U.S. market researcher.
</P>
<P>
Growth of e-commerce is accelerating worldwide, IDC said,
predicting that by the end of this year, 29 percent of people who
go online will purchase a good or service. That percentage will
swell to 38 percent by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Not only is the number of Web purchasers growing, so is the
size of the average transaction. According to IDC, all this growth
will translate into 1.6 trillion U.S. dollars being spent on
Internet commerce in 2003.
</P>
<P>
"This increased likelihood to buy will be driven by greater
availability of products, improved buyer confidence in security,
and enhanced local language sites for international buyers," said
the report based on 40,000 interviews in 31 countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another study released Monday by U.S. Internet
marketing research firm Greenfield found that the percentage of
online American consumers is down compared with a year ago. Of the
3,000 interviewees, 78 percent shopped online and 70 percent
bought online in the first quarter of this year, compared with 86
percent and 74 percent, respectively, for the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The primary reason recipients gave for curbing their shopping
habits was shipping, according to Greefield's study. Shoppers do
not want to pay the shipping costs involved with buying online.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, online auctions are growing in popularity in the
United States. The percentage of consumers participating in
auctions grew 4 percentage points from last year, from 40 percent
to 44 percent, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
Greenfield also found that "click-and-mortar" operations or
those with online and offline outlets appear to be winning the
battle for consumer confidence. In fact, 43 percent of American
online consumers are more comfortable purchasing from online
retailers that have an offline store nearby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
