<HEADLINE> Four Rebel Boats, Two Naval Craft Sink in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Four Tamil rebel boats and two Sri
Lankan naval craft Monday sunk in a clash off the country's north-
eastern coast, the Daily News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan navy attacked a cluster of Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) boats off Vettilikerni Monday and sank four of
them, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE deployed more boats in the confrontation during which
two naval craft were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
A search operation was launched to rescue the crew of the two
naval craft.
</P>
<P>
Since government forces suffered reversals in April this year,
the fighting in the peninsula has been fierce both on land and at
sea.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has reportedly warned the government forces to quit
the peninsula but government troops decided to ignore it and has
expressed the determination to hold on to the Jaffna peninsula,
the former Tamil rebels' stronghold, which it lost to the troops
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a 17-year-old war for a separate
state for the Tamil community in the country. An estimated 60,000
people have been killed in the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
