<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Indonesia Governor Named Suspect in Bank Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia Governor Syahril
Sabirin was named a suspect in the Bank Bali scandal for allegedly
violating the central bank's prudential principle in its policy to
reimburse interbank loans guaranteed by the government, national
newspapers reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But no travel ban has been imposed on Sabirin.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin was named a suspect following interrogation by
prosecutors on Monday afternoon. According to the newspapers,
Sabirin left the Attorney General's Office compound Monday night
after being questioned by prosecutors for almost six hours.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin's status as a suspect was not unexpected as prosecutors
had previously pointed to glaring inconsistencies in his testimony
with those of other witnesses over whether or not he attended a
February 11 1999)meeting at a Jakarta hotel which allegedly led
to the reimbursement of funds from Bank Indonesia to Bank Bali for
defaulted loans.
</P>
<P>
The scandal revolves around Bank Indonesia's reimbursement of
904 billion rupiah (129 million U.S. dollars) in defaulted loans
to other banks. Some 546 billion rupiah (78 million U.S. dollars)
of the money was then paid to PT Era Giat Prima for helping Bank
Bali recoup the money. There is suspicion that a large portion of
the money went to help bankroll then president B.J. Habibie's
renomination bid.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General's Office spokesman Yushar Yahya said Monday
that Sabirin had been named a suspect because he accelerated the
reimbursement of the money to Bank Bali, the clearance of which
some believe was conducted through questionable negotiations
between state officials and businessmen.
</P>
<P>
During a late night media briefing on Monday, representatives
for Sabirin attacked the allegations, accusing the government of
fabricating charges to remove the central bank governor.
</P>
<P>
"The governor confided (in us) that he had several times been
given a choice, both directly by the president and the attorney
general or other parties, to either resign and be appointed an
ambassador or be named a suspect," Bank Indonesia's deputy
director for legal affairs Amir Sjarifuddin was quoted by the
Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid and House of Representatives
Speaker Akbar Tandjung have urged the central bank governor to
quit, pending the corruption investigation. The president
reportedly told Sabirin to resign or risk being named a suspect in
the Bank Bali scandal.
</P>
<P>
Wahid earlier said that all state officials implicated in cases
under investigation should resign to facilitate the legal process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
