<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Report Says Mexico Turning Into Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 5 (Xinhua)-- Over half of Mexico's land is "
turning into desert," said the United Nations Organization (UN).
</P>
<P>
Mexico will attend World Environment Day with some of Latin
America's most worrying ecological indicators, said the UN in its
report "Latin America and the Caribbean: Environmental
Perspectives," published Monday.
</P>
<P>
In this study, it is affirmed that 60 percent of Mexico's land
is affected by severe or extreme land degradation, 30 percent by
hydride eroding and 43 percent by eolic erosion.
</P>
<P>
Besides problems of desertification, 19 percent of the capital'
s population suffer from breathing difficulties, conjunctivitis
and migraines due to the air's poor quality, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, like Peru, is facing "moderate" pressure from a fresh
water shortage, as it consumes each year 15 percent of its
reserves, it added.
</P>
<P>
Until 1995, Mexico was the only country on the American
continent that consumed more than 10 percent of its territory's
fresh water, it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
