<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Bars From Han Dynasty Unearthed In Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A total of 219 gold bars made during
the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220 A.D.) have been discovered in the
northern suburban of Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
A bulldozer driver unearthed the ingots while working at a
construction site. They were located in two separate containers,
both five meters underground.
</P>
<P>
Each of the bars has a diameter ranging from 5.6 cm to 6.5 cm
and weighs between 250 and 300 grams.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists also found some Chinese surnames such as Huang,
Zhang, Ma, Bei and Ji inscribed on the gold bars.
</P>
<P>
After some research, experts confirmed that the site where the
bars were stored is some five km away from the imperial palace of
the Han Dynasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
