<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's UTJ Party to Support Early Election Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel's United Torah Judaism
(UTJ) party announced Tuesday that it would support an early
election bill submitted by an opposition legislator.
</P>
<P>
All of UTJ's five members of the Knesset (Parliament) would vote
in favor of the bill, if it comes up for voting in the Knesset on
Wednesday, the party said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The ultra-Orthodox Shas party, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
largest coalition partner, also threatened on Tuesday to topple the
government by voting in favor of the bill which asks for dissolving
the parliament and holding early elections.
</P>
<P>
The bill was prepared by opposition legislator Avigdor
Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
Shas Knesset member Yair Perez said Tuesday that he has been
asked to mobilize the party's legislators to vote in favor of the
bill, which is expected to come up in the Knesset for a preliminary
reading on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Shas Chairman Eli Yishai, who returned home Tuesday evening from
Geneva, said that all its 17 Knesset members would vote in favor of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
Up to now it is not certain whether Lieberman will ask the
Knesset to vote his bill, and local political analysts said that
Lieberman would withdraw his bill if it is not guaranteed a
majority of 61 votes in the 120-member Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Barak and the Shas leadership took a rapid turn
for the worse on Monday. Responding to a Shas threat to vote for
the bill if Shas' demands for more funding to its ailing
educational system are not met, Barak called off government
negotiations with Shas over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Shas has 17 seats in the Knesset. Its defection would upset the
68-52 majority of Barak's coalition, already weakened by the
National Religious Party which disagrees with Barak's peace
policies.
</P>
<P>
Barak declared that he is not prepared to conduct negotiations
that are accompanied by Shas' threats, even if the threats are
implicit.
</P>
<P>
Shas' educational system is deeply indebted due to its poor
management over the past few years. Education Minister Yossi Sarid
refused to allocate more funds until Shas improves its management
and fires corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
Shas wants Barak to order Sarid to transfer millions of shekels
to its cash-strapped school system. And this dispute has been
dragging on for months without a proper settlement.
</P>
<P>
Shas' spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadiah Yosef, who has a final say
over all party issues, has nevertheless not instructed the party's
lawmakers how to vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
