<HEADLINE> Clinton Tries to Create Best Environment for Israeli-Palestinian Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said on
Tuesday that the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have reached a
critical moment for resolving difficult issues and making
difficult decisions.
</P>
<P>
"We're down now to the difficult issues and to the difficult
decisions," he told reporters at the White House ahead of his
talks with Jordan's King Abdullah. He promised to "create the best
possible environment" for the Israelis and Palestinians to work
out a framework for a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, now in the Middle East
to try to revive Mideast peace talks both on Israeli-Palestinian
track and on Israeli-Syrian track, announced on Tuesday that
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will hold peace talks near
Washington next week and Clinton said he was "encouraged" by
Albright's mission in the region.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who met Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak last week,
will also meet Palestinian President Yasser Arafat on June 14 in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Asked about whether he planned a Camp David-style session,
Clinton said he would await Albright's return, but first he would
have "a lot to discuss" with King Abdullah on the Mideast peace
process, he said.
</P>
<P>
"His Majesty and I are going to talk today. So after that, we'
ll make some decisions about what to do next," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said both Israel and the Palestinians should be
prepared to compromise before they could reach some agreement.
</P>
<P>
"I've been told by an old friend of mine that the best solution
is one that both sides are a bit unhappy about, which means that
both sides have had to give up something," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"And I think that when we look at final status, both sides have
to be very open-minded about the other people's position," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
