<HEADLINE> Security Council Condemns Fighting in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Council demanded an immediate cessation of hostilities and
reiterated its call for the demilitarization of the area as agreed
to by both governments, it said in a press statement after hearing
a briefing on the DRC by U.N. Assistant Secretary-General for
Peacekeeping He di Annabi.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council believe that armed engagements
between the two foreign armies of Rwanda and Uganda on the
territory of the DRC in violation of the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of this country are incompatible with the
Lusaka Ceasefire Agreement and unacceptable," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Mission to the DRC reported that fighting broke out in
Kisangani Monday and continued Tuesday with four people, including
two U.N. staffers, injured by glass splinters and falling debris.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, efforts by the neutral facilitator, former President
Ketumile Masire of Botswana, to carry out his mandate regarding
the inter-Congolese dialogue have run into difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The DRC Government has refused to take part in the preparatory
committee convened by Masier in Contonou, Benin, Monday and
Tuesday, and representatives of civil society and political
parties from the DRC have not been allowed to leave the country to
participate in the meeting, according to Annabi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
