<HEADLINE> Moderate Earthquakes Hit Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Two moderate earthquakes hit
Mexico Tuesday, but no victims or material damage have been
reported so far.
</P>
<P>
The first one measuring 4.4 degrees on the Richter scale
occurred at 12:03 local time in the south of Oaxaca state, south
of the country, said the National Seismological Service.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake in Oaxaca had its epicenter between the towns of
San Miguel Panixtlahuaca and Tataltepec de Valdez in the south of
the state.
</P>
<P>
The earth movement was felt strongly in the district of Jugila
and the state capital of Oaxaca, some 333 kilometers south of
Mexico City, said sources of the civil protection authorities.
</P>
<P>
Oaxaca is the state with larger seismic activities in the Latin
American country. So far this year, 115 tremors under 5 have been
registered, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The second earthquake of 4.7 degrees happened at 13:25 local
time in the coast of Colima state, east of the country, reported
the service, indicating the epicenter was along the coast.
</P>
<P>
Both states are situated in front of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
</TEXT>
