<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundian President to Visit S. Africa to Promote Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Burundian President Pierre
Buyoya will visit South Africa on Wednesday, which is believed to
be just another step towards restoring peace in his country, an
expert said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"His discussion with mediator Nelson Mandela will be one of the
many more to come," said Hannelie de Beer who is working at the
Institute for Security Studies in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
She said one could safely assume that Buyoya and his Defense
Minister Cyrille Ndayirukiye will come to Johannesburg to learn
from South Africa's experience in military integration.
</P>
<P>
The talks come ahead of a planned visit by Mandela to Burundi
later this month to meet armed groups and people in the country's
controversial regroupment camps.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's office Monday disclosed that the former South African
 president's visit to Bujumbura would last three days beginning
from June 12.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who was appointed chief facilitator late last year,
said last week that he would urge the Burundian government to lift
restrictions it had imposed on the political opposition and
members of the media.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Mandela held separate closed-door discussions with
Burundian government representatives and rebel groups to secure
support for his peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
Central to Mandela's plan was a 15-point document for peace
based on proposals from delegations to earlier rounds of peace
talks in the northern town of Arusha, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is aiming for a final round of negotiations in July
which he hopes will result in a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
de Beer, an expert in African conflicts, predicted that efforts
to peacefully resolve the conflict between Hutu rebels and the
Tutsi-dominated government would be a drawn-out process.
</P>
<P>
"It will take time for the warring parties to learn to trust
each other," she said.
</P>
<P>
War broke out in the tiny central African country in 1993,
pitting several rebel Hutu factions against the Tutsi-dominated
government and army.
</P>
<P>
Hutus, mostly peasant farmers, represent 85 percent of Burundi's
 population.
</P>
<P>
Mandela last week rejected the rebels' demand that their forces
should constitute 70 percent of the army.
</P>
<P>
It would be best if the country's army is 50 percent Hutu and
50 percent Tutsi, with representation for other minorities, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
