<HEADLINE> Ugandan Troops to Leave Congo if Security Ensured: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has declared that the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) will
leave the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) once Uganda's
legitimate security concerns are met within a regionally and
internationally recognized framework.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks Tuesday afternoon when
delivering the State of the Nation Address at the International
Conference Center here during the opening of the fifth session of
the Sixth Parliament.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the way forward for the DRC lies in the
implementation of the Lusaka peace agreement which was signed by
all belligerents in July and August last year.
</P>
<P>
A UPDF vehicle was attacked in the Kisangani city of the DRC
Monday morning. Later the UPDF and the Rwandan Patriotic Army
(RPA) were involved in skirmishes which still continued Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
According to Museveni, the skirmishes were started by the RPA
who fired on and completely destroyed the UPDF vehicle on its way
back from Bangoka airport to a UPDF base across the town.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. observers were this time able to see for themselves
that the trouble was started by the RPA, the president said,
adding that the RPA's provocation forced the UPDF to move and put
a front at Tchopo bridge following which the RPA launched 12
attacks on the UPDF.
</P>
<P>
Both Uganda and Rwanda have their troops stationed in Kisangani
where they back rival rebel factions fighting against President of
the DRC Laurent Kabila. 
</P>
