<HEADLINE> Protests Over Petrol Price Hike in Nigeria Spread to Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Protests over a 50 percent petrol
price rise in Nigeria, the largest oil-producing country in
Africa, entered the second day on Tuesday and spread to the
country's capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here from the capital, protesting
workers in the capital blocked the main access road to the
presidential villa and barred government workers from entering
their offices.
</P>
<P>
The protesters demanded an immediate reversal of the prices and
vowed to resist any hike.
</P>
<P>
The protests began on Monday across southwestern Nigeria ahead
of a planned strike by the Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC) on
Thursday over the hike.
</P>
<P>
Most of the gas stations in Lagos remained shut on Tuesday and
car petrol peddlers seem to be having their good time on the
streets of the largest city in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government last Thursday increased the country's
petrol price by 50 percent to 30 naira (100 naira equals about one
U. S. dollar) per liter.
</P>
<P>
The decision had met with mixed reactions in the country.
People in the business sector generally welcomed the move despite
the costs added to their operation, saying it is inevitable to
reduce the huge amount of money spent on subsidizing for a low
petrol price.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Information Minister Jerry Gana Monday said the hike
was caused by the country's heavy reliance upon foreign petrol
imports and mismanagement of its own petrol refineries.
</P>
<P>
The hike was justified by the billions of naira to be saved,
which could be used to reduce poverty and achieve universal
education, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
