<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Companies Found Hard to Keep IT Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen percent of the U.S.
workforce is continually in transition between jobs, which creates
an intensely competitive labor market, pushing up the cost of
staffing and retention, a U.S. market researcher said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The situation is especially true in information technology (IT).
International Data Corporation said in a report released Tuesday
that attrition is the single largest contributor to the IT skills
and staffing shortage in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Companies in the 21st century not only have to deal with a
momentous lack of skilled IT workers," said the report, "they also
have to learn how to manage a significantly changing workforce.
The way work will be accomplished this millennium will be very
different than in the past because of a very different workforce."
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, the report said, individual interests have replaced
trust and loyalty as the primary reasons for employees'
association with companies. According to IDC, downsizing, resizing,
rightsizing and reengeneering employee jobs for the sake of
improving the bottom line contributed to eroding employee trust
and loyalty.
</P>
<P>
"The available workers in the 21st century will expect and
demand individual accommodation with regard to their needs for
security, predictability, and dignity," said the report. "The
balance of power will shift entirely from the employer to the
employee in the United States."
</P>
<P>
Within IT, e-commerce is perhaps the hottest jobs. According to
a recent report by the Information Technology Association of
America, Web-related skills are now required for 13 percent of the
country's 10 million IT jobs.
</P>
<P>
The same is true in many other countries. As companies around
the globe scramble to establish their presence online, they are
desperate for Web and e-commerce developers, Internet security
professionals and project managers.
</P>
<P>
IDC's recommendations for attracting IT talent include
transferring organizational power to the employees and sharing
profits. IDC also suggests companies and employees take extra time
to make sure the employee and company fit well together during the
hiring process to reduce attrition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
