<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama, US Sign Treaty for Return of Cars, Airplanes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA, June 6 (Xinhua)-- Panama and United States signed
Tuesday "Treaty for Return of Vehicles or Airplanes" stolen or
illegally appropriated.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Foreign Minister in charge of Panama,
Harmodio Arias Cerjack and U.S. ambassador in Panama, Simon Ferro,
at this isthmus' country's capital.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian Foreign Minister in charge saw as successful the
accord's signing, saying that both countries are in process of
perfecting bilateral relations following giving back of Panama
Canal on December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
On his part, America's ambassador said the theft of vehicles or
airplanes is the third most profitable crime at international
level after drug trafficking and money laundry.
</P>
<P>
By this treaty, both countries have committed themselves to
return vehicles or airplanes registered, titled or provided with
documents and are on territory of one of the contracting parties.
</P>
<P>
Each government will designate a central authority which will
take care of dealing with notifications and requests conforming
with the procedure established in the treaty.
</P>
<P>
This accord was signed due to both governments admitting
thieving, robbery and illegal appropriating of vehicles and
airplanes through international borders is always more common.
</P>
<P>
The accord has been signed by Dominican Republic, Costa Rica,
Guatemala, among others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0337 </DOCNO>
