<HEADLINE> Britain Calls For Ban on Sierra Leone's Diamonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Tuesday called for a ban
on the export of diamonds from rebel-held areas of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook told the House of Commons that
Britain is pressing for an international trade embargo on diamonds
from Sierra Leone, a former British colony.
</P>
<P>
He said the trade in diamonds in Sierra Leone is fueling the
civil war in that Western African nation.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that Britain was exploring with its partners at the
United Nations Security Council a resolution banning the trade in
diamonds from Sierra Leone except where they are certified as
legitimate by the country's government.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the parliament, the foreign secretary
revealed that he is to visit Sierra Leone for a meeting on
Thursday with President Ahmad Tejan Kabba to discuss what else the
United Kingdom could do to help.
</P>
<P>
Cook said diamonds had fueled the rebellion for the past nine
years.
</P>
<P>
The people of the country were among the poorest in the world
yet the rebels could purchase vast quantities of arms, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ultimate objective was for the government of
Sierra Leone to take control of the diamond-mining areas, but that
in the short term the trade in illicit stones needed bringing
under control.
</P>
<P>
Britain will push for a diamond trade code of conduct at a July
meeting in Japan of foreign ministers from the Group of Eight (G-8)
leading industrial nations in the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 Group consists of Britain, Canada, France, Germany,
Italy, Japan the United States and Russia. The group is scheduled
to hold a summit in Japan next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
