<DOCNO> XIE20000606.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell Tuesday as
investors took profits from the previous gains.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 79.73 at 10735.57
and the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 65.39 at 3,
756.37.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor
's 500 index fell 9.79 at 1,457.84.
</P>
<P>
The market fell as investors took profits to lock in some gains
from the previous rally. The Dow index rose 292.97 points and the
Nasdaq composite rose 420.85 points in the previous three sessions.
</P>
<P>
Investors sold stocks that were seen as vulnerable to economic
slowdowns today. Last week, several economic reports showed the
signs of economic slowdowns under pressures of higher interest
rates and the reports propelled stocks higher.
</P>
<P>
J.P. Morgan fell today because hither rates is bad for
investment banking revenue. Wal-Mart and Circuit City were also
lower in reasons that weak economy means less profits for
retailers as consumers cut their spending.
</P>
<P>
But some big technology stocks advanced today. Microsoft and
Qualcomm rose.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 2.16 at 653.00 and the Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies fell 1.65 at 511.65. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 7.61 at 928.18.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,526 up, 1,407 down and 492
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 936.11 million shares from 831.31
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
